[White "1) Ideas connected to ...g5-g4"]
[Black "Diagram 1"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b3k1/2p1n1bp/p2p1nqr/RN1Pp1p1/1PP1Pp2/3N1P2/4BBPP/3Q1R1K b - - 0 21"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ White is already threatening Nxc7, destroying Black's queenside. You can defend the pawn, but in the King's Indian we attack on the kingside, and in many cases, we just ignore the hanging pieces on the other flank... }
21... g4
{ This is the typical breakthrough, Black wants to open files against the white king. }
22. Nxc7
{ The a8-rook is hanging. Would you go away with it or continue the assault on the kingside?   We will have a look at  22.fxg4  in one of the next puzzles. }
22... Rxh2+
{ Definitely, we choose to attack on the kingside by sacrificing the rook in order to create the typical mating threat: the pawn on g3, queen on the h-file, and ...Qh2 mate. }
23. Kxh2 Qh5+
{ If you wanted to play  23...g3  , it is more than fine as well. After  24.Kg1  Qh5  , we transpose to the main line. }
24. Kg1 { Now we only have to create the mate on h2 by playing the next move. }
24... g3 { A lot of beautiful combinations are based on this simple motif. }
25. Re1 { Clearing the way for the king to f1. } 25... Qh2+ 26. Kf1 Qh1+
{ What happens after  27.Bg1  is the subject of the next exercise. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
