[SetUp "1"]

{ You may think the attack has been parried since Black hasn't got more reasonable checks, but one of Black's pieces will save the day. Who can join this glorious battle attacking the most vulnerable pawn on the kingside? }
27... Bh3
{ 0-1 Murray-Hazai, Parkes op 1993. What a beautiful attacking move that brings White to heel! }
28. gxh3 { Otherwise, the mate on g2 is inevitable. } 28... Qxh3# *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Ideas connected to ...g5-g4"]
[Black "Diagram 1B"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b3k1/2p1n1bp/p2p1nqr/RN1Pp3/1PP1Ppp1/3N1P2/4BBPP/3Q1R1K w - - 0 22"]
[SetUp "1"]

22. fxg4
{ White allows the black knight to come with tempo, and the target is the h2-pawn. }
22... Nxg4 23. Bg1
{ It seems that White successfully defends the kingside, but the bishop is an overloaded piece if you look at the position carefully. It has to protect the h2-pawn and the e3-square. How can we profit from this fact? }
23... Rxh2+
{ Black sacrifices the rook in order to deflect the bishop from the protection of the e3-square. }
24. Bxh2 Ne3
{ This is the point, White has no defense against the threats: ...Qxg2 mate, and ...Nxd1 winning the queen. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Ideas connected to ...g5-g4"]
[Black "Diagram 2"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bq1r1k/1p4b1/p2p1n2/3Pp1pp/4Pp1n/1QN2P1P/PPRBBNP1/2R3K1 b - - 0 20"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ It seems that White is well-prepared against the typical attacking move ...g5-g4. There are more defenders, so should we prepare our push on the kingside or bravely attack without any hesitation? }
20... g4
{ That's right, Black sacrifices the pawn in order to open up the g-file. Don't be afraid of sacrificing your pieces, especially if it is just a little pawn. Play without fear in the King's Indian! }
21. fxg4 hxg4 22. hxg4
{ Black wants to bring the queen to the kingside, but the knight is standing in its way. How can we clear that diagonal without losing any tempi? }
22... Nxg4
{ The idea behind this temporary piece sacrifice is to open the h4-d8 diagonal so that the queen from g5 can attack the white piece on g4. Even the prettiest combinations are based on elementary mating motifs. If the queen is on g5 and the knight is on h4, there is the threat of the ...Qxg2 mate.   22...Bxg4  instead allows White to defend with  23.Bxg4  Nxg4  24.Ncd1!  ,  preparing Qh3. }
23. Nxg4
{ 23.Bxg4  is less logical because after  23...Bxg4  24.Nxg4  Qg5  , the knight cannot go back to protect  the g2-pawn. }
23... Bxg4 24. Bxg4 Qg5 { We will continue this exercise in the next diagram. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Ideas connected to ...g5-g4"]
[Black "Diagram 2A"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r4r1k/1p4b1/p2p4/3Pp1q1/4PpBn/1QN5/PPRB2P1/2R3K1 w - - 0 25"]
[SetUp "1"]

25. Bh3
{ The bishop has left the d1-h5 diagonal, so Black can continue the attack. }
25... Nf3+ { 26.Kh1  is running into a mating attack after  26...Qg3  . } 26.
Kf1
{ Black desires to blow up the whole kingside, but the knight hinders the push of the f-pawn. What should we do with it? }
26... Nxd2+
{ Killing two birds with one stone! We get rid of our knight and at the same time we eliminate the bishop, so it won't be able to create a pin on the c1-h6 diagonal. }
27. Rxd2
{ The time is right, Black can execute the original plan of blowing up the kingside. }
27... f3
{ That is what we wanted! The white king is in serious danger, not to mention the unprotected rooks on d2 and c1. }
28. Nb1
{ This sad retreating move is the only defense! The queen and the f8-rook are attacking the white king; who else can help them? }
28... Bh6
{ Now the bishop is much more active and ready to create an x-ray motif on the c1-h6 diagonal. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Ideas connected to ...g5-g4"]
[Black "Diagram 2B"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r4r1k/1p6/p2p3b/3Pp1q1/4P3/1Q3p1B/PP1R2P1/1NR2K2 w - - 0 29"]
[SetUp "1"]

29. gxf3
{ After this move, one of the white pieces has become unprotected. Which is this piece and how can we attack it? }
29... Qh4
{ The bishop is under attack, and the diagonal of the bishop has been opened. }
30. Bg2
{ It doesn't make sense dealing with those weak rooks, which are way more useless than the light-squared bishop. }
30... Bxd2 31. Nxd2
{ Materially, White is still better, but now comes the second wave of the attack. The f3-pawn is well-protected on the kingside, so it makes the rook useless on the f-file. Where can the f8-rook be better placed? }
31... Rg8 32. Qe3
{ The white queen is the new defender and it seems that Black's attack has been repelled. But Black has still got something in petto, using the beneficial position of the g8-rook. }
32... Rxg2
{ Eliminating the last defender; the black queen and rook are strong enough to continue the assault. }
33. Kxg2 Rg8+
{ Joining the other important piece into the attack with a check. } 34. Kf1
Qh1+ 35. Ke2 Rg2+ 36. Kd3 Qxc1
{ Black is again an exchange up, but the white queen is ready to give checks, which will lead to a drawish position:  37.Qh6+  Kg8  38.Qe6+  Kg7  39.Qe7+  Kg8  40.Qe6+  ,  with a repetition of moves. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Ideas connected to ...g5-g4"]
[Black "Diagram 3"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bq3k/1pn2rb1/pB1p2n1/P2Pp1pp/1P2Pp2/5P2/2Q1B1PP/2R1NRK1 b - - 0 22"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ White will win the piece back after taking the c7-knight, but in the King's Indian, in most cases, it doesn't bother us. But we do care about the attack on the other flank, so let's play the first and most important attacking move. }
22... g4
{ Without this aggressive move, Black won't have chances on the kingside. } 23.
Bxc7
{ Our decision is quite easy now since the most important attacking piece is hanging. }
23... Qh4
{ The next step is to play ...g4-g3, creating a mating threat on h2. } 24. Bxd6
{ White accepts the sacrifice and opens up the c-file for the heavy artillery. Black has to keep following the original plan, which is the preparation for the dangerous mating threat. }
24... g3 { This is the key move in Black's attacking plans. } 25. h3
{ If White chooses  25.Qxc8  , after  25...Rxc8  26.Rxc8  Rf8  , Black is winning.   After  25.h3  , White hopes that the kingside got closed, but maybe White hasn't counted on our beautiful attacker... }
25... Bxh3 { White's last defensive wall is blown up! } 26. gxh3 Qxh3
{ The g3-pawn, the queen, and later the knight from h4, can effectively work together against the white king. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Ideas connected to ...g5-g4"]
[Black "Diagram 3A"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r6k/1p3rb1/p2B2n1/P2Pp2p/1P2Pp2/5Ppq/2Q1B3/2R1NRK1 w - - 0 27"]
[SetUp "1"]

27. Bd1
{ The idea behind this move is to open up the 2nd rank so then the queen can defend the h2-square. But it is quite passive at the same time and gives Black good chances to continue the attack. How can we improve the position of our pieces? }
27... Nh4
{ This is the ideal attacking setup for the black pieces. There is a tough fight for the g2-square. }
28. Qb2
{ This is the most persistent defense, counterattacking on e5 and opening up the diagonal for the bishop. }
28... Re8 { Simply protecting the e5-pawn. } 29. Ba4
{ Our rook is hanging, so we have to make a decision. Should we escape with our rook, or open up the g-file no matter what? }
29... g2 { Of course, we choose to push our g-pawn! } 30. Nxg2
{ Where would you put the hanging e8-rook? } 30... Rg8
{ Obviously, on the vital g-file, creating a nasty pin. } 31. Rc2
{ White has to defend the knight from the 2nd rank. But at the same time, White cannot protect one of the pieces. }
31... Nxf3+
{ Finally, Black gets some material back, and no pawns remain to defend the white king. White has to sacrifice an exchange to avoid the immediate collapse of the position. Materially, it will be close to equal, but Black still keeps a strong attack. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Ideas connected to ...g5-g4"]
[Black "Diagram 3B"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r6k/1p3rb1/p2B2n1/P2Pp2p/1P2Pp2/5Ppq/2Q1B3/2R1NRK1 w - - 0 27"]
[SetUp "1"]

27. Bc4
{ As we'll see later, the bishop is much more active on c4 than on d1. The bishop is annoying on d6 because it is putting pressure on the e5-pawn, so Black has to chase it away. }
27... Rd8
{ Forcing away the bishop from the attack of the e5-pawn. It is quite an important move as if we start with the most natural-looking move  27...Nh4  , White can play  28.Qb2  immediately, attacking  the weakened e5-pawn. }
28. Bc5
{ The queen and the g3-pawn are not enough, so it's time to bring the next piece into the battle! }
28... Nh4
{ After inserting the previous moves, the e5-pawn is not a target anymore. }
29. d6
{ Opening up the a2-g8 diagonal. On the one hand, White is attacking the rook and creates danger with the d6-passed pawn. But on the other hand, it forces the black rook to maneuver to the g-file. How can we get to that vital file? }
29... Rf6
{ Now Black wants to concentrate the rooks on the semi-open g-file and play ...g3-g2. }
30. Qb2
{ This is a difficult move to find, White wants to play Rc2, overprotecting the second rank. Before White can execute this plan, we bear down on our enemy. Our plan is easy: we would like to push the g-pawn. Is it necessary to prepare it by ...Rg6 or not? }
30... g2
{ Of course not, that is the spirit of the position! After ...g2, we're not just opening up the g-file, but the f3-pawn becomes the next target too. }
31. Nxg2
{ As I have mentioned, the rook belongs to the g-file, so let's put it there! }
31... Rg6
{ The rooks belong to the open files, they are very aggressive attacking monsters, and using them for passive defense would be a waste of their strength. }
32. Rc2
{ Defending the g2-knight from the side. We have reached the ideal position with our pieces, and now we can focus on the next target. Which white piece's fate has been sealed? }
32... Nxf3+
{ It is time to harvest the material and weaken even more the white king's position.   After  33.Rxf3  Qxf3  34.Rf2  ,  White wants to bring the queen to defend from e2.  34...Qxe4  35.Qe2  ,  forcing the exchange of queens is usually a big achievement for White. Without queens, it is very difficult to continue the attack. Following  35...Qxe2  36.Bxe2  Bf8  37.Bxh5  Rg3∞  ,  White has two minor pieces for a rook and a pawn, and the endgame is very complicated. On the other hand, exactly this is what Black wants in the King's Indian: wild tactical complications, where a mistake may come very easily. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Ideas connected to ...g5-g4"]
[Black "Diagram 4"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2q1bk1/pp1b2rp/3p1nn1/PN1Pp1p1/1P2Pp2/5P2/4BBPP/2RQNR1K b - - 0 20"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ The white knight has left the defense of the e4-pawn. Black's typical breakthrough is ...g5-g4. Although, the g4-square is well-defended and the a7-pawn is hanging... Do all these things stop the push of the g5-pawn? }
20... g4
{ This mighty push is possible because if White takes the pawn, the e4-pawn will fall. }
21. Nc7
{ This knight penetration is one of the main ideas of White's play. The a8-rook is hanging and Ne6 may force to exchange the dangerous light-squared bishop. The latter can cause a lot of trouble for Black since that bishop is the heart and soul of the attack in these kinds of positions. Can we do anything against these threats? Or should we continue the attack on the kingside? }
21... g3 { Sure, we have decided to focus on the kingside! } 22. Nxa8
{ If White chooses to play  22.Bg1  , which is an inaccuracy, Black plays  22...gxh2  , and later the plan  is ...Nh5. There is no going back now for Black... }
22... gxf2 23. Nc7
{ White wants to keep the active knight with the idea of jumping on e6 or trying to exchange Black's mighty bishop via Bb5.   Had White played  23.Rxf2  Qxa8  would have come. }
23... fxe1=Q { How to take back on e1? } 24. Qxe1
{ This is the better recapture because the queen defends the vital e1-h4 diagonal. Let's open up the h4-d8 diagonal so our queen will also control the h4-square. }
24... Nh5 { Now Black's plan has to be the opening of the g- and h-files. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Ideas connected to ...g5-g4"]
[Black "Diagram 4A"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "3q1bk1/ppNb2rp/3p2n1/P2Pp2n/1P2Pp2/5P2/4B1PP/2R1QR1K w - - 0 25"]
[SetUp "1"]

25. Ne6
{ We usually want to keep our light-squared bishop alive, but sometimes it is not possible. }
25... Bxe6 26. dxe6
{ Now our aim is to open up the g- and h-files. If it costs a piece, then it is more than fine! }
26... Ng3+ 27. hxg3 fxg3 28. Qxg3
{ The queen is in danger because of the rook on g7, but first, we need to move our knight. }
28... Nf4
{ By sacrificing the knight, Black has opened up the g-file and attacks the queen and the g2-pawn. The white queen is attacked. In most cases, we move the queen away. However, we always need to look for exceptions, for a strong zwischenzug. }
29. Bc4
{ Creating nasty threats on the a2-g8 diagonal. Black cannot take the queen because e6-e7 wins the queen back and even gives life to a new one!   29.Qf2  would have been a mistake because of  29...Rg6  . We have to leave this dangerous diagonal. }
29... Kh8 30. Qh2
{ The white queen has to defend the h-file. How can we create a threat against the white king and queen? }
30... Rg6
{ The plan is obviously ...Rh6. White has to give up the queen but later gets enough compensation for the sacrificed piece. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Ideas connected to ...g5-g4"]
[Black "Diagram 4B"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "3q1bk1/ppNb2rp/3p2n1/P2Pp2n/1P2Pp2/5P2/4B1PP/2R1QR1K w - - 0 25"]
[SetUp "1"]

25. Bb5
{ Exchanging the bad bishop for the good one certainly favors White and here Black cannot avoid this. }
25... Bxb5 26. Nxb5
{ Now we will see the benefit of holding our knight on h5! } 26... Ng3+
{ This is not the only move, but by far the most attractive one! In our course, if we have a choice, we always go for the spectacular sacrifice if it has about the same value as the quiet positional move. }
27. hxg3 fxg3 28. Qxg3
{ The queen on g3 is vulnerable, how can we immediately attack it? } 28... Nf4
{ Black has sacrificed the knight in order to open up the g-file and attack the main target: the g2-pawn. }
29. Qh2
{ White has to control the h-file even at the expense of a queen sacrifice! How can we create a threat against the white king and queen? }
29... Rg6
{ Black is going to win the queen, but White will get a good equivalent − two rooks for it. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Ideas connected to ...g5-g4"]
[Black "Diagram 4C"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2q1bk1/ppNb2rp/3p1nn1/P2Pp3/1P2Pp2/5Pp1/4BBPP/2RQNR1K w - - 0 22"]
[SetUp "1"]

22. hxg3
{ White unnecessarily opens up the kingside, allowing Black to finish the game with an irresistible attack! If you are thinking about ...fxg3 you are right, it is good, but can we find a better move? Can you bring another piece into this fight attacking the g3-pawn? }
22... Nh5
{ There is always a choice between ...fxg3 and ...Nh5, and there is no rule about which can be the better move. }
23. g4
{ The next move is a one-second decision in a real game since going back is a no way! }
23... Ng3+ 24. Kg1
{ The knight is excellent on g3, attacking the e2-bishop, and the knight on c7 can be in trouble because of the g7-rook. How can we open up the 7th rank attacking the defender of the e2-bishop? }
24... Ba4
{ Winning material. Of course, other moves like  24...Qh4  , etc, also lead to winning positions. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Ideas connected to ...g5-g4"]
[Black "Diagram 4D"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2q1bk1/pp1b2rp/3p1nn1/PN1Pp3/1P2Ppp1/5P2/4BBPP/2RQNR1K w - - 0 21"]
[SetUp "1"]

21. Nxa7
{ White wins the pawn but allows the typical continuation of the attack. What would be your next move? }
21... g3
{ The g3-pawn is a dangerous beast, and it cannot be taken twice because the a7-knight is hanging. }
22. Bb6
{ The bishop has to keep the g1-a7 diagonal. Black has to make a decision about where to put the queen. How can we keep an eye on the a7-knight with the queen? }
22... Qe8
{ Controlling the b5-square means that the a7-knight remains trapped. } 23. Rc7
{ The rook looks quite aggressive on c7, but we have to keep calm and focus on our usual plan. One of the knights' position can be improved, which one and how? }
23... Nh4 { This is the most active square for the knight. } 24. Qc2
{ Black's next move is a prophylactic one, so it is not easy to find since we are waiting for a tactical phenomenon. }
24... Kh8
{ In some cases, we open up the 7th rank and it is of high importance not to allow Rxg7 with check. That is how we prepare nice combinations. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Ideas connected to ...g5-g4"]
[Black "Diagram 4E"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r3qbk1/NpRb2rp/1B1p1n2/P2Pp3/1P2Pp1n/5Pp1/4B1PP/3QNR1K w - - 0 24"]
[SetUp "1"]

24. Rxb7 { How should Black continue the attack? } 24... Qh5
{ What is White's best defense in these types of positions? } 25. Rxd7
{ Eliminating the dangerous bishop is of high importance. Now finding Black's reaction is far from easy, especially if we are obsessed with the material.   25...Rxd7  would be the most natural reply, but that's not how we want to play! We want to focus all of our forces on the h-file. }
25... Rg6
{ This is indeed a wonderful move! Instead of taking the rook, Black focuses on the mating threats! }
26. Rg1
{ Black has no more decisive attacking moves on the kingside, so the next move is easy to find. }
26... Nxd7 { Now Black can calmly continue the attack on the h-file. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Ideas connected to ...g5-g4"]
[Black "Diagram 4F"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r4bk1/N2R3p/1B1p1nr1/P2Pp2q/1P2Pp1n/5Pp1/4B1PP/3QNR1K w - - 0 26"]
[SetUp "1"]

26. h3
{ White has no time for this type of defense because Black can finish the rook maneuver, preparing mating threats. }
26... Rh6 27. Kg1
{ This no escape from trouble! Let's start destroying White's defensive wall! }
27... Nxg2 28. Nxg2 Qxh3 { The mate is inevitable now. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Ideas connected to ...g5-g4"]
[Black "Diagram 4G"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r4bk1/N2R3p/1B1p1nr1/P2Pp2q/1P2Pp1n/5Pp1/4B1PP/3QNR1K w - - 0 26"]
[SetUp "1"]

26. Bg1
{ The d7-rook is still hanging, but Black will keep the pace of the attack. There are always two targets: the g2 and the h2-pawn. Which one would you take? }
26... Nxg2 { This is the best move, opening up both g- and h-files. } 27. Nxg2
{ It goes without saying that although the d7-rook is still en prise, Black concentrates on the kingside attack... Now the g2-knight is on our radar because the rook is indirectly attacking it. Who else can help the rook attack the g2-knight? }
27... Qh3 { ∆ ...gxh2 } 28. Bb5 gxh2 29. Rf2
{ Let's finish the original plan of focusing all of our forces on the h-file! }
29... Rh6
{ Of course,  29...hxg1=Q  @@StartBracket@@Q or R@@EndBracket@@ would have been good as well. }
