{ The c5-knight is attacked and most of the players would defend it without any hesitation. What do you think about that? Would you protect your knight or have a deep breath and start the offensive on the kingside? }
19... g4
{ It is unbelievable, but the breakthrough on the kingside is so important that Black is not bothering with the knight! }
20. Bxc5 { Continue what you have started! } 20... g3
{ The g3-pawn itself creates dangerous mating threats if the queen gets to h4. }
21. hxg3 { This is the only way to free the white pieces around the king. }
21... fxg3 22. f4
{ Remember this pretty escape. In many positions, it will be White's only hope. Before White plays Nf3, let's bring our queen into the battle! }
22... Qh4 23. Nf3
{ White's dark-squared bishop protects many important squares, we should get rid of it. }
23... Bxc5+ 24. Rxc5
{ We would like to keep our queen on the h-file, what is the most proper square for it? }
24... Qh6
{ Now we understand why was ...Bxc5 important. The h6-queen is attacking on the c1-h6 diagonal without forgetting about the h-file. }
25. f5 { Let's activate our queen! } 25... Qe3+ 26. Kh1 Qh6+
{ Black has to give the perpetual checks. Many combinations may only lead to a draw but after beautiful fireworks! }
