25. Nca7
{ White wants to eliminate the fearsome c8-bishop, but ignoring the dangerous g4-pawn leads to a winning attack for Black. }
25... g3 { The g3-pawn creates a lot of mating threats. } 26. Be1
{ Now comes the typical piece sacrifice, destroying the white king's shelter. }
26... Bxh3 27. gxh3
{ The fight for the crucial g2 and h3-squares continues. Let's give a chance for one of the black pieces to attack it. }
27... Nh4 { This is the knight's best place for the attack. } 28. Qc2
{ Now Black has to bring the heavy artillery to the g-file, preparing the final push ...g3-g2. }
28... Qg7 { ∆ ...Kh8 and ...Rg8. } 29. Ra2
{ White wants to overprotect the second rank since ...g3-g2 may come at any moment. }
29... Kh8 { ∆ ...Rg8 } 30. Bd3
{ Opening up the 2nd rank for the queen and the rook. } 30... Rg8
{ Black is ready for the final blow of ...g3-g2. } 31. Nc6
{ Sooner or later the knight has to come back to the fight. } 31... g2 32. Rf2
{ How can we chase away the white monarch from the g1-square? } 32... Qg3
{ ∆ ...Qh2! The mate is already inevitable. } 33. Nc3 Qh2+ 34. Kxh2 g1=Q# *

