27. Bf3
{ White blockades the f3-square but allows Black to get total control over the h-file. Let's bring our mighty heavy artillery! }
27... Qh6 { Black has a devastating attack on the h-file. } 28. Re1
{ The white king wants to run away towards the center via Kf1-e2. After this move, there is no point in bringing our rook to the h-file, as by doing this, we would punch into the air.  In these cases, we need to find new plans and set the old ones aside. The f3-bishop defends the g4 and e4-pawns, can we attack it somehow? }
28... Nh4 { Of course, we can! } 29. Nd8
{ White has attacked the rook, do we care about this? } 29... Nxf3+
{ No, we don't. We can feel that our attack will crush through. } 30. gxf3
{ Now the prettiest win is the typical breakthrough on the kingside. White's kingside pawns seem to secure the escape of the king. We need to weaken this 'strong' pawn formation with a typical piece sacrifice. }
30... Nxg4 31. fxg4 { Let's finish what we originally planned on the h-file! }
31... Rh7 { 0-1 Finke-Wieringa, corr 1995. } *

