30. Nxc7
{ White ignores the threat against the h3-pawn because by taking the c7 one, White goes for a big fish, the a8-rook.  It seems that the rook is trapped, but Black doesn't care and has to find the decisive breakthrough on the kingside by opening diagonals, activating both the bishop and the knight at the same time. }
30... f3
{ What a wonderful zwischenzug again! Black creates a mating threat by ...Qxh3, opens up the c1-h6 diagonal, and vacates the f4-square for the knight. }
31. Bxf3 { Black continues the assault, the a8-rook is not important at all. }
31... Qxh3 { The threat is ...Bf4 followed by ...Qh2 mate. } 32. Bg2
{ The queen has to go back, let's confront White with a tough decision regarding the c7-knight. }
32... Qh7 { Where to go with the knight? } 33. Ne6
{ The g4-pawn is more important than the whole rook. White closes the diagonal of the c8-bishop. At first sight, it seems that the queen is far away from the fight, but from h7 it can still create a mating threat with another piece. }
33... Bf4 { A simple ...Qh2 mate is the threat. } 34. Nxf4
{ White eliminates the dangerous attacker, the bishop on f4, but the knight will replace it with great effect. }
34... Nxf4 35. Bg3 { Activate the last undeveloped piece! } 35... Bxg4
{ It happens often in the King's Indian that the c8-bishop doesn't make a move for a long time, but the decisive blow is delivered by it!   After  36.Bf3  ,  Black obviously doesn't want to exchange the beautiful bishop.  36...Bh3  37.Bxf4  @@StartBracket@@If White plays  37.Re1  Qg7  comes and Black's attack crashes through.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r5k1/7q/2Np1n2/3Pp3/P3PB2/5B1b/8/3Q1RK1 b - - 0 37@@EndFEN@@  37...exf4  38.Rf2  Re8-+  and the e4-pawn cannot be protected anymore so White's position collapses. }
