[White "1) Ideas connected to ...g5-g4"]
[Black "Diagram 8"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1R2brk/1p6/p2p1n2/q2Pp1pp/4Pp1n/1Q3P1P/PP2BNP1/2RN2K1 b - - 0 23"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ White has just taken the c8-bishop, and the a8-rook is hanging. Most of the players would take back on c8 without any hesitation. Instead of that, a brilliant 'zwischenzug' is coming! }
23... g4
{ Don't waste your time dealing with your hanging pieces, just open up the g-file!   23...Rxc8  and then ...g4 looks like the most natural move order, exchanging the rook first and then executing the breakthrough on the kingside. However, after the opening of the g-file and the pushing of the f4-pawn, it is crucial to keep White's rook on c1 because ...Bh6 would come with tempo, attacking the c1-rook. }
24. hxg4
{ If White plays  24.fxg4  ,  that gives Black an extra opportunity to open up the c1-h6 diagonal after  24...f3  ,  with the plan of ...Qe1+ followed by ...Bh6. The a8-rook is still hanging, but Black follows the plan. }
24... hxg4 25. fxg4
{ We have arrived at a moment when the pawn is no longer on f3, which means we can use the previously mentioned plan of opening up the c1-h6 diagonal. }
25... f3 { That's right, now the bishop will be very active in a few moves! }
26. Bf1
{ 26.Bxf3  looks more natural, but it allows the penetration of the black queen to the first rank. }
26... fxg2
{ White cannot take back on g2 because of the previously mentioned reason; the queen can give a check on e1 and White's position collapses. }
27. Qh3
{ This is a typical defensive move in the King's Indian. The queen is one of the best defenders. }
27... Bh6
{ Now the passive bishop becomes the pride of Black's position.   After  27...Bh6  28.Qxh4  gxf1=Q+  29.Kxf1  Rgxc8  ,  the g8-square has to be vacated for the king.  30.Qxh6+  Nh7  31.Rxc8+  Rxc8∞  and Black is an exchange up, but because of the shaky king, this is not enough to play for a win. }
*

