[SetUp "1"]

24. Rxa8
{ Taking the rook would be the player's first thought, but it leads to a quick catastrophe on the kingside. Activate the queen! }
24... Qe1+
{ Now the queen is destroying White's defensive wall. The bishop needs to interfere on f1, as otherwise,  25.Kh2  g3  is a beautiful mate! }
25. Bf1
{ It was a necessity, but now the bishop cannot defend one of the most important pawns on the kingside. Which is this pawn and how can we continue the winning attack? }
25... Nxf3+
{ The f3-pawn was it! We open up the g-file in a forced way and activate the g8-rook. }
26. gxf3 gxf3+ 27. Kh2 Qxf1 { The mate is inevitable so Black is winning. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Ideas connected to ...g4-g3"]
[Black "Diagram 1"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bq3k/pp2n1bp/3p1nr1/1N1Pp3/1P2Ppp1/1Q1N1P2/P3BBPP/R1R3K1 b - - 0 19"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Although White is threatening the knight's jump to c7, Black can continue with the typical attacking plan on the kingside. }
19... g3
{ The major attacking plan for Black in the King's Indian main line − this time, without sacrificing the pawn. }
20. hxg3
{ There is no real alternative to this move because if the bishop leaves the g1-a7 diagonal, then White loses material:  20.Be1  Qb6+  and the knight on b5 falls.   Continuing the original plan of  20.Nc7  simply loses after  20...gxf2+  21.Nxf2  and  21...Rb8  . }
20... fxg3 { Again,  21.Be1  would be a blunder because of  21...Qb6  . } 21.
Be3
{ Our aim is to open up the h4-d8 diagonal for our queen, but there are too many knights on that diagonal. Do we have time for normal knight moves like ...Nh5 or do we have to choose the most aggressive sacrifice in order to get extra tempi? }
21... Nfxd5
{ Not a real question, that's for sure. We definitely would like to play like this in the King's Indian! We again choose the most beautiful move for our main line! The main idea behind this move has been mentioned @@StartBracket@@opening the h4-d8 diagonal@@EndBracket@@, but it is a deflection at the same time. Of course, ...Bh6 and ...Ne8 are also good. }
22. exd5
{ Now the question is which piece has been deflected? And why was it important anyway? }
22... Nf5
{ This is the point; the e4-pawn was deflected and now there is a wonderful square on f5 for our knight to jump into. Black wins a tempo opening up the d8-h4 diagonal, and now the queen is ready to finish the attack. }
23. Nc7
{ If White plays  23.Bd2  to save the dark-squared bishop, we can bring the queen into the attack by playing  23...Qh4  , and Black is winning. So White wants to find some counterplay after this move, but it is already too late because we go for our aim on the kingside. Many pieces are hanging, but there is something that is more important than material. }
23... Qh4 { Black is not wasting time with the a8-rook or the e3-bishop. } 24.
Nxa8 Nxe3
{ Don't let the king escape via f1-e1-d2 and create an immediate mate threat! Nothing matters when we have such a strong attack against the white king. }
25. Rxc8+ Bf8
{ White has an extra rook and a piece, but the mate is inevitable. } 26. Rxf8+
{ Now our only task is to interfere on the 8th rank and there is no other weapon White can use against us. }
26... Rg8 27. Rxg8+ Kxg8 { Mate is coming on the next move. } *

