[SetUp "1"]

{ Black has good attacking chances on the kingside. What is the standard procedure? }
21... g3
{ This pawn is the heart and soul of the attack. There are two major targets, the g2 and the h2-pawns. }
22. hxg3
{ If White plays  22.h3  with the idea of closing the kingside, we know that there is no escape from trouble. We have the beautiful light-squared bishop, which can destroy any hope. }
22... fxg3 { White has a very important and typical defensive resource now. }
23. f4
{ By opening up the d1-h5 diagonal, the light-squared bishop now takes part in the defense. The f1-rook can also help and the f3-square can be a good defensive post. Black still wants to reach the h4-square with the queen, and both knights are hindering this lethal threat.  Again, don't feel sorry for your knight! Just keep your original plan in your mind and do everything you can to succeed! }
23... Nxe4
{ Black sacrifices the knight in order to bring the queen to the desired h4-square. On top of that, by eliminating the e4-pawn creates a wonderful square for the knight on f5. }
24. Nxe4 Nf5 { With the double threat of ...Qh4 and ...Ne3. } 25. Bg4
{ Here we see the bright point of 23.f4. The bishop will close the h-file via Bg4-h3, but this can't stop us! }
25... Qh4 { Threatening mate in one on h2. } 26. Bh3 Ne3
{ Continued in the next puzzle. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Ideas connected to ...g4-g3"]
[Black "Diagram 2A"]
