[SetUp "1"]

{ This position comes from Nachev-Zimmerman, Sochi 2005. Black didn't find the typical attacking move, but you are capable of that. }
18... g3
{ White is already a pawn up, and now Black sacrifices the second one. The King's Indian is really suitable for attacking players! }
19. hxg3 fxg3 20. Bxg3
{ The bishop has become vulnerable on g3, so let's bring another piece into the battle attacking that bishop! }
20... Nh5
{ The knight takes the position for the forthcoming attack, and the h4-d8 diagonal is now open for the queen. }
21. Bf2
{ The white bishop is better on the g1-a7 diagonal for the queenside attack. On the other hand, the f4-square lacks any protection now. There is no better time to call our mighty queen into battle!   21.Bh2  leaves the g1-a7 diagonal for Black's disposal, and especially the e3-square becomes weak, so Black plays  21...Bh6  . }
21... Qg5
{ Now the queen is also on its best square; the targets are g3 and the g2-pawn. }
22. g4
{ White wants to close the g-file, and the g4-pawn is now heavily defended. Because of the pin on the g-file, our h5-knight is not in danger, so the other knight can jump its dream square. }
22... Ngf4 { This is the best attacking square for the knight. } 23. Nxc7
{ Give a check to the white king! } 23... Nh3+
{ We'll examine this position in the next puzzle. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
