{ The c-file is open and White is ready to assault on the queenside with Nb5. The threats are real, either to jump with the knight on c7 or to take the a7-pawn. Should we do something against it, or continue the attack on the kingside? }
19... g3
{ As in most cases, Black again ignores the danger on the queenside. By sacrificing the pawn, suddenly all the black pieces are in an aggressive mode. }
20. hxg3 fxg3 21. Bxg3
{ As usual, after this pawn sacrifice the bishop becomes vulnerable. Let's attack it! }
21... Nh5
{ Black is not only attacking the bishop but also opens up the h4-d8 diagonal for the queen. The f4-square will be wonderful for a knight, the rook goes to g7, and the bishop can be activated via h6. Black gets all these gains for only one humble pawn! }
22. Bf2
{ As we have seen in the previous examples if the bishop goes back to h2, Black can play ...Bh6, controlling the important c1-h6 diagonal. This is the natural retreat, White wants to control the important g1-a7 diagonal but the continuation is the same. }
22... Bh6 23. Rd1 { Which piece can join the attack? } 23... Qg5
{ Of course, the queen! Black has a strong attack against the g2-pawn using the weaknesses of the dark squares f4 and g3. }
