20. Be1
{ White wants to avoid opening up the files and diagonals, but this passive retreat is not solving all the problems. Bring the knight to the best-attacking square! }
20... Nh5 { Now the h4-d8 diagonal is open for the black queen. } 21. h3
{ If White wants to close the position, then this is the only option. Unfortunately, White cannot avoid the sacrifice on h3. But before we completely destroy this pawn formation on the kingside, we need to put more pressure on these pawns! }
21... Nh4 { The last preparatory move before the firework. } 22. Bf1
{ Protecting g2 and h3 but leaving the f3-pawn unprotected. The overloaded piece is the g2-pawn defending both the h3 and the f3-pawns. What pawn should we take first? }
22... Bxh3
{ If we take the f3-pawn first, White plays gxf3 and the h3-pawn is protected by the f1-bishop. }
23. gxh3 Nxf3+ 24. Kh1
{ We really would like to push the f-pawn; which piece is blocking it? } 24...
Nd4 { A lot of pieces are hanging, but the biggest threat is ...f4-f3. } *

