{ White has achieved some progress on the queenside. The a7-pawn is hanging and in case of the natural  18...a6  , the weakness  of b6 begins to tell after  19.Bb6  . How can Black show that on the other flank, Black is the master? }
18... g3
{ By sacrificing a pawn, Black gets a lot of squares, files, and diagonals for the pieces. }
19. hxg3 fxg3 20. Bxg3
{ White has got an annoying knight on b5, let's do something with it! } 20...
a6
{ By sending the knight back, Black wins a couple of tempi until White again creates some real threats on the queenside. }
21. Na3 { The white knight wants to come back via Na3-c4-b6. } 21... h4
{ Creating a wonderful post for the knight on h5. } 22. Bf2
{ White wants to hold the g1-a7 diagonal, but now the f4-square becomes even weaker.   If White plays  22.Bh2  , Black can play the extremely strong  22...b5!  move. This is a well-known motif with the idea of  putting the a3-knight on the shelf. Just place your pieces on the well-known squares where they can have a huge role in this attack! }
22... Nh5 23. Nc4 Ngf4
{ ∆ ...Qg5, and the target is not only the g3-square but the g2-pawn as well. }
