[White "2) Ideas connected to ...g4-g3"]
[Black "Diagram 7"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bq2k1/pp3rbp/3p1nn1/1N1Pp3/4Ppp1/3N1P2/PP1QBBPP/2R2RK1 b - - 0 18"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ The a7-pawn is hanging and many players would simply react with  18...a6  . Is there a more forceful way to attack on the kingside? }
18... g3
{ Black wants to create weaknesses in White's defensive pawn structure on the kingside by this typical sacrifice. }
19. hxg3
{ In this situation, Black always has two options: to take back on g3 or play ...Nh5. There is no rule about it, the answer depends on concrete calculation. }
19... Nh5
{ In this case, the immediate knight attack looks more profitable.  19...fxg3  is the usual reply opening up the position on the kingside. This is also possible, but perhaps not as strong as the main line. }
20. gxf4
{ White allows more black pieces to invade the kingside. How should Black take back on f4?   If White tries to keep the kingside closed as much as possible with  20.g4  , then Black has  20...Ng3  followed by ...Qh4. }
20... Ngxf4 { With the g6-knight because our plan is ...Bh6 and ...Rg7! } 21.
g4
{ This is the last chance for closing the kingside. Our knight is under attack, what should we do about it? }
21... Bh6
{ Absolutely nothing! Black is not worrying about the knight and goes for a bigger target, the d2-queen. }
22. Kh2
{ Running out of the ...Nh3 check. But it doesn't bother us, we just calmly continue our original plan. }
22... Rg7
{ The h5-knight still cannot be taken because if White does it, ...Qg5 comes and mate is inevitable. }
23. Rc2 { Now let's create nasty threats with the bishop by protecting it! }
23... Bg5 { Now the bishop is protected, so the f4-knight may jump anywhere. }
24. Qd1 { Leaving the nasty c1-h6 diagonal. Free the f4-square! } 24... Nxe2
25. Rxe2
{ Before the knight occupies the f4-square, we should deal with the b5-knight. }
25... a6 26. Nc3 Nf4
{ Followed by ...h7-h5 and the kingside will be opened up. } *

