{ White was clearly successful on the queenside by opening the files and diagonals and winning the exchange. Black desperately needs to create counterplay on the kingside. }
22... g3
{ This is the typical advance, provoking a lot of weaknesses on White's kingside. }
23. hxg3
{ Now Black has to make the choice between two promising alternatives,  23...fxg3  and  23...Nh5  . }
23... Nh5
{ In this case, probably both are about the same value, but there is no rule on how to find the best one. Only concrete calculation can show the right way. }
24. gxf4 { Now Black can establish a marvelous knight on f4. } 24... Ngxf4 25.
g4
{ Closing the g-file is the best that White can do, but it leaves the h3-square unprotected. }
25... Nh3+ 26. Kh2 Nxf2 27. Rxf2
{ Now, as you can see, the rook on f2 is not defended; use this fact to find the next move! }
27... Bxg4
{ White is still an exchange up but can only save their skin with a very precise defense. }
