25. Nd3
{ White is seeking relief by exchanging one pair of knights but leaves the g2-square unprotected. }
25... Nxg2 { Now Black can develop the attack on the open g- and h-files. } 26.
Kxg2 Qg5+ 27. Kh1
{ The next step is to force the white king to the g-file; how can we do that? }
27... Qh6 { Forcing the white king to the g-file. } 28. Kg2
{ Now it would be nice to force the white king to the h-file. Which piece can do that? }
28... Bh3+
{ 28...Bf6?  was winning in case of 28.Kg1, but here White has an extra possibility of  28.Rg1! }
29. Kh1 Bxf1 { Not only taking the rook but opening up the h-file as well. }
30. Bxf1 { Give a double check! } 30... Ng3+ 31. Kg2
{ Now comes a nice example for a possible chapter of 'chasing the king'. }
31... Qh1+ { Forcing the king to move towards Black's army. } 32. Kxg3
{ We really would like to bring our rook via the g-file. How can we prepare ...Rg7? }
32... Bf6 { ∆ ...Rg7, with a quick mate. } *

