[SetUp "1"]

{ The white knight has just taken on d6, and Black's position looks collapsing. The only chance is a desperate counterattack on the kingside. }
21... g3
{ By sacrificing the second pawn, Black creates excellent practical chances. }
22. hxg3 { Black has the famous choice between  22...fxg3  and  22...Nh5  . }
22... Nh5
{ In this case, the text move is the better one. After  22...fxg3  23.Bxg3  Nh5  24.Bh2  Bh6  , Black has some compensation, but after for instance  25.Nc4  , White is to be preferred. }
23. gxf4 Nhxf4 24. Nxf4 Nxf4 25. Rc2
{ White defends not only the e2-bishop, but the whole 2nd rank. The knight on d6 can be vulnerable because the black queen indirectly attacks it. What should we do with the d7-bishop? }
25... Bh3 { The bishop cannot be taken because of ...Qg5 and ...Qg2 mate. } 26.
Nf5
{ The knight is coming back to the defense. Do we want to live together with such a forceful knight? }
26... Rxf5
{ No! Black eliminates the good defender and continues the attack against the g2-pawn. }
27. exf5 Bxg2
{ Black has eliminated the g2-pawn, so the white king is in serious danger. } *

