28. Rfc1
{ White wants to double the rooks on the c-file, hoping for penetration on c7 or c8. But Black just wants to focus on the kingside with the pieces. }
28... Qg5
{ Black now creates real mating threats but leaves the back-rank undefended. }
29. d6+ Kh8 30. Rc8+ { Now comes White's counterattack. } 30... Bf8
{ Here, White has a brilliant defense decoying the black queen. } 31. Bh4
{ 31.Rxb8??  would be a huge mistake because  31...Bh3  comes with a mate in a few moves. }
31... Qxh4 32. Qe3
{ The queen is usually a very good defender, Black now has to take the draw. }
32... Qh1+ 33. Kf2 Qh4+ { Black has no more than perpetual checks. } *

