[SetUp "1"]

{ White has just attacked the a8-rook and many players would move it away without thinking. What is your opinion about that? }
20... g3
{ This is the zwischenzug Black has to think about in every moment in the King's Indian. When a piece is attacked, the first idea has to be a counterattack and not a passive retreat. }
21. Nxa8
{ Now Black can take both pieces and get a small material advantage. Will you take them immediately? }
21... Nh5
{ However, this second zwischenzug is far from trivial. Instead of taking the pieces, Black goes for the well-known mating attack with ...Qh4. }
22. Qc2 gxf2+
{ The most aggressive move  22...Qh4?  is losing after  23.h3  Bxh3  24.gxh3  Qxh3  , where White can exchange the queens after  25.Qc8  . }
23. Rxf2 Qxa8
{ There is a big difference compared to the immediate capture on f2 on move 21. The knight is a dangerous attacking piece on h5, meanwhile, the queen on c2 is irrelevant. }
24. b5
{ White has always some chances on the queenside and has to open files for the rooks. }
24... axb5 { 24...Bf6  followed by ...Bh4 looks strong too. } *

