[SetUp "1"]

{ The a8-rook is hanging, and it seems that White came first on the queenside. Black's chances lie on the kingside. How can we continue the attack? }
21... g3
{ Black has to react very quickly and has no time to think about the a8-rook.   Black can also start with  21...b3  , which is an intermediate move showing that the pawns with a death sentence can be extremely dangerous. }
22. Nxa8
{ White takes the rook, hoping for a possible queen sacrifice on c8, eliminating the dangerous light-squared bishop. }
22... Qh4 23. h3
{ Now comes the beautiful motif: Black opens up the h3-c8 diagonal for the bishop and doesn't want to allow 24.Qxc8 at the same time. }
23... Nc5
{ Sacrificing the knight, but closing the c-file and winning a tempo for the next sacrifice. }
24. Bxc5 { Now Black destroys the last barricade of pawns. } 24... Bxh3 25.
gxh3 Qxh3 26. Bd1
{ White opens up the 2nd rank to defend against the mate on h2. } 26... Bxc5+
27. Nxc5 { Black now brings the last remaining forces into the battle. } 27...
Nh4
{ There is no defense against ...g3-g2. Now White has to find the counterattack, otherwise, the king gets mated. }
28. Qb2 { There is no going back now, let's continue what we have started! }
28... g2 29. Qxe5+ Rg7
{ Both players are forced to repeat moves and draw with perpetual checks:  30.Qe8  Rg8  31.Qe5=  , with a repetition of moves. }
*

