[SetUp "1"]

22. hxg3
{ It is understandable that White wants to get rid of the mighty g3-pawn. On the other hand, it opens up the position for the black pieces. }
22... fxg3 23. Bxg3
{ Now again Black can start the offensive with a zwischenzug on the other flank. }
23... b3 24. Qc3 b2
{ Black wants to deflect the queen from the defense of the c7-knight. } 25. Rc2
{ White keeps the rook alive, which can protect the 2nd rank. The a8-rook is still not the main character in the play.   If White plays the natural  25.Qxb2  , then  25...Bxc7  comes. Now Black has to focus on White's unprotected bishop. }
25... Qg5
{ Black ignores White's threats on the queenside and has to come with the pieces against the white king. }
26. Bh2
{ Surprisingly enough the well-defended e5-pawn can be a target, so the bishop keeps an eye on it. Our well-known dark-squared bishop is a bit passive, let's change this! }
26... Nf6 { Black has to concentrate all the forces on the kingside. } 27. Qxb2
{ 27.Nxa8  is too greedy, and the punishment is quick and efficient after  27...Bh3  , when  White cannot protect the g2-pawn because then the b2-pawn will promote to a queen! Now there are two heavy pieces on the g-file, but someone is blocking the cooperation between them. Which piece has to be removed? }
27... Nf4 { The knight is very strong, White has to exchange it. } 28. Nxf4
exf4 { Clearing the way for the bishop to e5. } 29. Rf2 Be5 30. Qb4
{ The queen and the rook are attacking the weak g2-pawn; is there any other piece to do so? }
30... Bh3 31. Bf1 { And finally Black has time to save the rook! } 31... Rad8
{ The chances are equal in a very complicated middlegame. } *

