{ The a8-rook is hanging and many players would just react to the threat by moving it away to a safe place. In the King's Indian, one tempo can be decisive, and the question is: who comes first with the attack? }
20... g3
{ Black continues the typical attack as if nothing happened on the other flank. }
21. hxg3 { The g3-pawn is too dangerous, it has to be eliminated. } 21... fxg3
22. Bxg3 { As usual, the bishop is quite vulnerable on g3, let's attack it! }
22... Nh5
{ Opening the h4-d8 diagonal and forcing White to choose between two retreating moves with the bishop. }
23. Bh2 Bh6
{ The bishop joins the attack on the c1-h6 diagonal with great effect. White has a nice defensive move here, creating some space around the king. }
24. f4
{ Opening up the d1-h5 diagonal, the f-file, and freeing the f3-square for the pieces. }
24... Ngxf4 25. Bxh5
{ Now Black opens up the c1-h6 diagonal and the f-file at once. } 25... Nh3+
26. gxh3 Be3+ { Here the bishop is more valuable than the c1-rook. } 27. Kg2
Qg5+ { All the black pieces join the attack with tempo. } 28. Bg4 Rxf1 29. Kxf1
Rf8+
{ Now White's only chance is to sacrifice back the material.  30.Qf3  ,  otherwise, Black will give mate very quickly.  30...Rxf3+  31.Nxf3  Qg6  32.Bxd7  Bxc1  33.Bf5  Qh6∞  .  White has three pieces for the queen, and the chances are about equal. }
