20. Qd2
{ White wants to keep the kingside as closed as possible. The bishop is quite annoying on h4, how can we get rid of it? }
20... Ng6 21. Bxf6
{ 21.Bg5  would be a mistake because of the well-known tactical motif  21...Nxe4  . Three pieces can take the bishop back, which is the most effective one? }
21... Rxf6 { The rook! The plan is ...Nh4, ...Rh6, then later ...Qh4. } 22. Ra2
Nh4
{ ∆ ...Rh6. This is a very funny way of forcing White to accept the pawn sacrifice on g3. }
23. hxg3 fxg3 24. Qg5
{ There is a double attack against the unprotected h4-knight and the g3-pawn. }
24... Ng6 25. Qxg3
{ Finally White had to take the pawn, and now the dark squares on the kingside are very weak. Later, Black wants to put the knight on f4, and we should prepare this! }
25... Kh8
{ Leaving the pin on the g-file and preparing the activation of the minor pieces via ...Bh6 and ...Nf4. }
26. Qe1 { Soon or later the queen has to leave the g-file. } 26... Bh6
{ Black has a wonderful play on the dark squares, he may use e3, f4, g5, g3 and h4 for his plans. }
