{ White pushes the pawns on the queenside and Black advances on the kingside. Who comes first? }
17... g3 18. Bg1
{ Black usually focuses on the kingside and doesn't bother with the losses on the queenside. But the exception proves the rule... }
18... dxc5
{ Black opens the c5-f8 diagonal for the white bishop and on top of that lets the bishop attack the f8-rook. On the contrary, if the f8-rook is taken, the black bishop will control the vital diagonals from c5. But if White has to go back with the c5-bishop, the d6-square will be a wonderful post for the black pieces, especially for the knight. }
19. Bxc5
{ Now Black can even force White to win the exchange, or just ignore the threat and improve the pieces. }
19... b6
{ Allowing or forcing the white bishop to take the f8-rook.   19...Ne8  is also a wonderful idea, fighting for the dark squares because after  20.Bxf8?  Qh4  comes and if White wants to close the kingside by playing  21.h3  Bxh3  blows up the pawn structure and Black is easily winning. }
20. Bg1 { We have one more pawn that is eager to fight! } 20... h4
{ ∆ ...h4-h3, opening up the files on the kingside. } 21. h3
{ This is the only defense, at least ...Qh4 is not possible. How can we put pressure on the h3-pawn? }
21... Nh7 { The plan is ...Ng5 and the sacrifice comes soon on h3. } 22. Qd2
{ White tries to control the 2nd rank after a piece sacrifice on h3. Let's play the last preparatory move leaving the sometimes dangerous a2-g8 diagonal! }
22... Kh8 23. Bd3
{ Opening up the second rank, but White's pieces are too passive. } 23... Ng5
24. d6 cxd6 { Now we see why was 22...Kh8 so cautious. } 25. a5
{ Opening the position on the queenside is very important for White, but it is just too late. }
25... bxa5
{ Black wants to avoid any problems on the queenside. We can totally focus on the attack on the other flank. }
