[FEN "r1bq1rk1/2p1n1bp/1p1p1n2/1N1Pp3/PBP1Pp2/3N1PpP/4B1P1/R2Q1RK1 b - - 0 19"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ White is ready for the advance on the queenside by a4-a5, and the kingside is fairly closed. Without a piece sacrifice, Black cannot continue the attack on the kingside. }
19... Bxh3
{ This is the thematic bishop sacrifice on h3, eliminating the defensive white pawns. If the queen can take on h3, the mating threats become real. }
20. gxh3 Qd7 21. Nf2
{ White sacrifices back the knight in order to free the other pieces. Most of the players would take the knight without hesitation. Is there any candidate move?   If White tries to defend the h3-pawn with  21.Kg2  , after  21...Ng6  22.Rh1  Nh4  23.Kg1  Nxe4!  24.fxe4  f3  , White is busted.   Note that  21.Qc2  with the defensive idea  21...Qxh3?!  22.Bd1!  followed by Qg2  , doesn't work since Black has better: @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/2pqn1bp/1p1p1n2/1N1Pp3/PBP1Pp2/3N1PpP/2Q1B3/R4RK1 b - - 0 21@@EndFEN@@  21...Ng6  first works wonders, when White cannot oppose further resistance in view of the  inevitable ...Nh4 and ...Qxh3. }
21... Ng6
{ 21...gxf2  22.Rxf2  creates more freedom around the king, the rook defends the 2nd rank, and the bishop  comes to f1. }
22. a5
{ White cannot do anything on the kingside and continues the plan on the queenside, opening files and diagonals. }
22... bxa5 23. Bxa5
{ 23.Rxa5  doesn't change the course of the game.  23...Nh4  comes and the knight controls  the g2-square, so ...gxf2+ is already a real threat. }
23... Nh4
{ 23...gxf2?  is again premature, because after  24.Rxf2  , the white pieces get more freedom for the defense. }
24. c5
{ White's attack on the queenside comes too late. Also, the pawn grab  24.Bxc7  fails in view of  24...gxf2+  25.Rxf2  Qxh3  26.Bxd6  Ng4!  The rook on f8 is en prise, so why not add another piece into the fire? Black has an overwhelming attack. For instance, after  27.fxg4  f3  28.Rxa8  Qg3+  29.Kf1  fxe2+  30.Qxe2  Rxa8  31.Na3  Bh6  , White is two pawns up but  with a lost position due to the ...Be3 threat. }
24... dxc5 25. d6
{ White wants to open up the queenside and the center in order to deflect the black pieces from the attack on the kingside. Now Black has done every preparation so finally the time has come to eliminate the most important defender. }
25... gxf2+ 26. Rxf2 cxd6 27. Nxd6
{ We need to place our king on a safe square, let's prepare this! } 27... h6
{ Black plans ...Kh7, where the black king is safe and ...Rg8 may come. We have an extra pawn and good attacking chances.   27...Qxh3?  works only for White after  28.Rh2  Qg3  29.Kh1  and the white king is much healthier than before. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) Sacrifice on h3"]
[Black "Diagram 2A"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r4rk1/2pqn1bp/1p1p1n2/1N1Pp3/PBP1Pp2/3N1PpP/4B3/R2Q1RK1 w - - 0 21"]
[SetUp "1"]

21. Kg2
{ White can temporarily protect the weak h3-pawn with the following Rh1, but the king is running into a bigger issue... }
21... Ng6 { The idea is ...Nh4+, winning some tempi for the attack. } 22. Rh1
{ This was White's idea: now the rook protects the weak pawn. } 22... Nh4+ 23.
Kg1
{ The h3-pawn is well-protected. Black has to find a new target and a new breakthrough is coming. We'll see this motif in a different chapter, which is based on the fact that we would like to free the f3-square for our pawn. }
23... Nxe4
{ Decoying the f3-pawn, and then the black connected passed pawns decide the battle. }
24. fxe4 f3
{ Although White is two-piece up for the moment, a lot of material will be lost soon to avoid the quick mate. For example,  25.Be1  is well met by  25...fxe2  26.Qxe2  g2  and White can resign in view of ...Rf1+, which will be delivered next. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) Sacrifice on h3"]
[Black "Diagram 2B"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r4rk1/2pqn1bp/1p1p1n2/1N1Pp3/PBP1Pp2/3N1PpP/4B3/R2Q1RK1 w - - 0 21"]
[SetUp "1"]

21. Qc2
{ White's plan is to follow up with Bd1, clearing the second rank for the queen. Now, the first idea is obviously ...Qxh3. Before we take there, let's think about candidate moves! }
21... Ng6
{ Planning ...Qxh3 followed by ...Nh4. The immediate  21...Qxh3  would be a mistake because after  22.Bd1  Ng6  , White comes first with  23.Qg2  since Black cannot exchange queens and has to retreat. }
22. Bd1 { Opening up the second rank for the defense. } 22... Nh4
{ 22...Qxh3?  transposes to 21...Qxh3. } 23. Nf2
{ White is again ready to sacrifice the knight back for some extra space for the remaining defenders. How can Black continue the attack against the weak h3-pawn?   Holding on to the material with  23.Ne1  spells trouble for White. After  23...Qxh3  24.Ra2  Nh5  , Black's threats  of ...g2 and the quieter ...Rf6 are impossible to meet. }
23... h5
{ Taking away the g4-square from the knight and preparing the knight maneuver ...Nh7-g5. }
24. Ra3
{ There is already no defense; at least White wants to protect the third rank. Prepare the attack against the h3-pawn! }
24... Nh7
{ Followed by ...Ng5 and perhaps further preparation comes with ...Kh8 and ...Rg8, conquering the g-file. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) Sacrifice on h3"]
[Black "Diagram 3"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b2rk1/Bp4b1/3p2n1/PN1Pp1np/4Pp1q/5PpP/1P2BNP1/2RQ1RK1 b - - 0 22"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ White has just won an important pawn on a7 and has an undisputable advantage on the queenside. This cannot be said about the kingside, where the black pieces as hungry sharks are gathering for a strong bite on the h3-pawn.  The f2-knight is hanging, but it cannot be taken because of Bxf2 and the queen on h4 is in trouble. So Black must focus on the weakest point in White's kingside pawn formation, which is obviously the h3-pawn. What should we do with it? }
22... Bxh3
{ Using the brute force method usually pays well in the King's Indian. } 23.
Nxh3 Nxh3+ 24. gxh3 Qxh3 25. Rf2
{ White has to sacrifice back a whole rook. White has got a very important dark-squared bishop, can we change this situation somehow? }
25... Rxa7
{ This is the point! The strong dark-squared bishop is dead now, and the a8-rook had no other role than sacrificing itself for the attack on the kingside. }
26. Rg2
{ White wants to save the last defender, the rook, but it cannot last long because another piece can join the attack with great effect!   26.Nxa7  is the subject of the next puzzle. }
26... Nh4 27. Bf1 Nxg2 28. Bxg2 Qh2+ 29. Kf1
{ Now Black can simply get an extra pawn on the other flank. } 29... Rxa5
{ Black had a big material advantage and a strong attack in Agashe-Milu, Baile Herculane 1994. }
*

