[White "3) Sacrifice on h3"]
[Black "Diagram 4"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b2rk1/Bp4b1/3p2n1/PN1P3p/4Pp1q/3N2pP/1P2B1P1/R2Q1RK1 b - - 0 22"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ White has an extra pawn and some small threats on the queenside, but the kingside is already in ruins. How can Black deliver a big punch? }
22... Bxh3 { Eliminating the defending pawns. } 23. gxh3 Qxh3 { ∆ Qh2# } 24.
Rf2
{ The only chance to avoid the mate is to sacrifice the rook. The f2-rook is hanging, but automatic captures are not always the best solution. In Diagram 3 we have seen a similar motif, eliminating White's beautiful dark-squared bishop. }
24... Rxa7
{ Black 'exchanges' the nice bishop for a useless rook.  24...gxf2?  allows the dark-squared bishop to return to the defense after  25.Bxf2  . }
25. Nxa7
{ Again think twice before you just take the rook with a check! The slightly more 'resilient'  25.Qf1  will be discussed next. }
25... Bd4
{ Pinning the rook is more forceful than taking it. A quick mate is coming. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
