[White "3) Sacrifice on h3"]
[Black "Diagram 5"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2b2rk1/1p4b1/1N1p2n1/P2Pp2p/4Pp1q/5PpP/1P2B1P1/R2QNRK1 b - - 0 23"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ White already has an extra rook and the bishop is hanging on c8, so this is the last chance for the typical piece sacrifice. }
23... Bxh3 24. gxh3 Qxh3 { ∆ Qh2# } 25. Rf2
{ As we have seen this several times, White has to sacrifice the rook back in order to avoid the mate. Now White hasn't got a dark-squared bishop protecting the f2-rook, so it doesn't make sense waiting with this move... }
25... gxf2+ 26. Kxf2
{ Now Black has to make a choice between two promising queen checks: ...Qh2+ or ...Qg3+? Only one is good! }
26... Qg3+
{ 26...Qh2?  allows White to bring the knight and queen to the defense.  27.Ng2  Nh4  28.Qh1  leads only to a very complicated fight. }
27. Kf1
{ Black has to bring a new piece into the fight. OK, but which one? You probably already know the answer since we have seen an identical position in Diagram 1... }
27... h4
{ Planning ...h3-h2 next, which looks a bit slowish, but White cannot do anything against it. }
28. Bb5 { Going for the Ke2 run towards the center. } 28... h3 29. Ke2 Nh4
{ ...h2 comes and soon the f3-pawn will fall. } *

