[White "3) Sacrifice on h3"]
[Black "Diagram 7"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r4bk1/Np1bqr1p/1B1p1nn1/P2Pp3/1P2Pp2/5PpP/4B1P1/2RQNRK1 b - - 0 22"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ White looks fairly successful on the queenside after winning the a7-pawn and is ready to penetrate with the rook to c7. White may believe that the kingside is closed, and Black's attack cannot be continued. Is that so? }
22... Bxh3
{ This is the typical destroying sacrifice in this type of pawn formation in the King's Indian. If the queen can take on h3, ...Qh2 mate is a brutal threat. }
23. gxh3 { Accepting the bishop sacrifice makes Black's task a bit easier. }
23... Qd7
{ The h3-pawn cannot be defended, so the queen will reach the ideal h3-square. }
24. Rc2
{ White wants to defend via the 2nd rank.  24.Qd2  was also an alternative. }
24... Qxh3 25. Bd3
{ Opening up the 2nd rank for the rook. Black now brings the remaining pieces for the attack. }
25... Nh4 { ∆ ...Rg7 and ...g3-g2. } 26. Nb5
{ There is nothing White can do against Black's plan. } 26... Rg7
{ The final blow is ...g2. } 27. Qd2
{ White desperately defends the 2nd rank, but cannot avoid fate. } 27... g2
{ Opening up the g-file and creating a nasty pin. } 28. Nxg2
{ How can the a8-rook join the attack? Maneuvering the rook to g8 looks rather time-consuming, what else can we do with that rook? }
28... Rc8
{ Black takes the c-file with tempo because if the c2-rook is not defending the 2nd rank, the mate is coming on g2. }
29. Nc7
{ Closing the c-file, but creating an additional target. Let's prepare ...Rg8! }
29... Be7
{ Black plans ...Kh8 and ...Rcg8 next, with a winning attack on the g-file. } *

