[SetUp "1"]

23. Rc7
{ White penetrates to the 7th rank attacking the queen and the b7-pawn, but this allows the h3-bishop to come back. }
23... Bd7 { The black queen has to find access to the h-file. } 24. Bb5
{ White wants to put pressure on the pinned bishop, and the f6-knight has to defend it, so the opening of the h4-d8 diagonal is not so easy. First, we need to secure the d7-bishop. }
24... Rd8
{ This looks like a simple defensive move, but wait, sacrifices will come soon! }
25. Rxb7
{ White has already two connected passed pawns on the queenside, the d8-rook is hanging, and the endgame is lost for Black. However, the time has come to put our queen on h4. }
25... Nh5
{ Black ignores the threat of Bxd8 and has only one goal: to get to h4 and give mate on h2. }
26. Rf2
{ Clearing the f1-square for the king but at the same time sacrificing the rook. }
26... gxf2+ 27. Bxf2 { Improve the position of the knight! } 27... Ng3 28. Bxd7
Rxd7 29. Rxd7 { Would you take the rook, or do something else? } 29... Qh4
{ Of course, we don't bother with the rook on d7! } 30. Bxg3 fxg3 31. Rxf7
{ Before we continue the attack against the white king, just get rid of the rook! }
31... Kxf7 { Black is winning. } *

