[SetUp "1"]

{ White has just taken the d6-pawn, and most of the players would take back automatically. Is there a beautiful zwischenzug? }
19... Bxh3
{ Instead of taking back without thinking, Black sacrifices the bishop understanding that time is the most important thing in this position.  19...cxd6  looks natural but gives White the opportunity to organize a defense on the 2nd rank after  20.Qd2  . }
20. gxh3
{ As you know already by heart, after the sacrifices on h3, the h3-pawn is Black's main target. }
20... Qd7 { Certainly, the h3-pawn is more important than the one on d6. } 21.
Qd2
{ We saw already the idea, White wants to defend on the 2nd rank. Now comes the big surprise! Black focuses only on the kingside ignoring the happenings on the other flank. However, we always need to concentrate on the whole board! }
21... c6
{ Suddenly, instead of  21...Qxh3  , which can be answered by  22.Bc4  , we change directions and attack White's hanging pieces on the queenside. }
22. Nc7 Rxa7
{ Winning back the piece and keeping the attacking chances on the kingside. }
23. Ne6 { The knight is wonderful here. Is it better than a rook? } 23... Qxd6
{ Black decides that yes, the knight is worth a rook in this special case. }
24. Nxf8 Bxf8
{ White is a clear exchange up, but Black has total control over the dark squares and will continue the attack against the white king. }
