[SetUp "1"]

{ The typical sacrifice on the kingside wants to destroy White's defensive pawn formation. Black usually concentrates on the kingside and ignores the threats on the other flank. This time the position requires a more complex approach. }
26... Bxh3
{ This is the starting move in most of the cases, with a quick win of the white h- and g-pawns. In this case, another tactical motif will help. }
27. gxh3
{ The h3-pawn can easily be defended, so Black has to find another target. }
27... Rc8
{ Suddenly the c7-bishop is pinned and White cannot protect it properly. } 28.
Ng2 Rfxc7 29. Qxc7 Rxc7 30. Rxc7
{ The queen is a very flexible piece, it can easily attack both flanks. The target is now on the queenside. }
30... Qd8 31. Rfc1
{ The king should leave the 8th rank to avoid motifs there. } 31... Kh7
{ ∆ ...Kh6, leaving the 8th rank and soon also the 7th one. The king will find eternal safety on the 6th rank. }
