[SetUp "1"]

{ Everything is ready for the big sacrifice on h3, as the queen and the rook are already on the h-file. The only obstacle is the d7-knight, but on a 'normal' knight move White can defend with Nf2. Black has to speed up the process... }
20... Nc5
{ Black sacrifices the knight preparing the next sacrifice on h3. The queen is now attacked, so White has no time to defend the h3-pawn with Nf2. }
21. bxc5 { The next sacrifice is not difficult to find. } 21... Bxh3 22. Kf2
{ The white king wants to run away from the kingside. Accepting the sacrifice with gxh3 makes Black's task easier after ...Qxh3, when mate is coming in a couple of moves. Black has to open up the position, following the 21...Bxh3 plan.   Trying to oppose resistance with  22.Nf2  fails in view of  22...Bxg2!  23.Ng4  Qh1+  24.Kf2  Qh3  25.Nxh6  Bxh6  . White is a rook up but that won't save the king... Following  26.Bc4  Bxf3  27.Rg1  g4  28.Ne2  , Black is spoilt for choice, but a cute way to win is  28...Nxd5!  29.Bxd5  @@StartBracket@@  29.exd5  Bg5-+  and White has to start giving back material to avoid getting mated.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r6k/1p5p/p2p3b/2PBp3/4Ppp1/1Q3b1q/P3NK2/2R1B1R1 b - - 0 29@@EndFEN@@  29...Qh2+  30.Kf1  Bxe2  . }
22... Bxg2 23. Rg1
{ The bishop was taboo because of the mate in one. It seems that the remaining black pieces cannot join the attack, but now comes another beautiful sacrifice which is based on the fact that we would like to make the central pawn go away. }
23... Nf5
{ The knight may jump on d4 attacking the queen, the bishop, and the f3-pawn. }
24. exf5 e4
{ Opening up the long diagonal for the King's Indian bishop, threatening ...Bd4, but ...e3 is also very uncomfortable. }
