[SetUp "1"]

{ Black has a dream of a ...Bxh3 sacrifice, when the heavy pieces on the h-file will launch a winning attack. White knows this and wants to sacrifice an exchange on c8, keeping the kingside formation safe. How can Black solve this problem? }
18... Nc5
{ Black has to close the c-file in order to buy time for the ...Bxh3 sacrifice.  18...Nf6  allows  19.Rxc8!  Nxc8  20.Nc7  , with a successful penetration  to the e6-square. Black won't have a piece to sacrifice on h3. }
19. Bxc5 { Do we take back on c5, or sacrifice another piece on h3? } 19...
Bxh3
{ Obviously, we continue our attacking plan on the kingside. We open up the h-file for the heavy artillery. }
20. Nf2
{ 20.gxh3  Qxh3  leads to a quick mate.  The h3-bishop is attacked, but is there anybody who is thinking about a retreat? }
20... Bxg2
{ This is the forceful move, destroying White's defensive pawn formation. } 21.
Ng4 { Protecting the h2-square, but abandonning the h1 one. } 21... Qh1+ 22.
Kf2
{ The white king wants to run away towards the middle via Ke1. Do we allow this? }
22... Qh4+ { Certainly not. The white king has to remain on the kingside. } 23.
Kg1
{ It is a real surprise if we move away an attacked piece, as  23.Kxg2  runs into  23...Qg3  . }
23... Rh5 { We need this beautiful rook for the attack. } 24. Qe1
{ What do you think about the exchange of queens? } 24... Qh1+ { No, thanks. }
25. Kf2 Qh3
{ ∆  26.--  Qg3  27.Kg1  Rh1  .   26.Bd1  avoids an immediate mate but does allow Black to start collecting material with  26...dxc5  while the white king is still not out of the woods yet. }
*

