{ White has won a pawn on the queenside, but the knight on a7 and the queen on a6 are far away from the kingside. Black has to be quick and efficient on the other side of the board. }
22... Bxh3
{ After this nice bishop sacrifice, the white king has no shelter anymore. }
23. gxh3 Rxh3
{ Black is ready to launch an attack on the open g- and h-files. } 24. Qb7
{ Now Black has to bring the queen to the g-file, but which square is the best one: g6 or g5? }
24... Qe8
{ The g6 is the right one, you will get the answer to your 'why' question very soon... }
25. Ng2
{ Now, let's push the dangerous f-pawn!   If White plays  25.Kg2  , we can reply with  25...Qh5  , defending the rook and  threatening ...Qg4+. That would have been impossible had Black tried to bring the queen to g5 by  playing @@StartFEN@@r2q2k1/NQp1n1bp/3p4/3Pp3/1P2Pp2/7r/P4B2/2R1NRK1 b - - 0 24@@EndFEN@@  24...Ng6  . Following  25.Kg2  , Black  suddenly has a problem with the h3-rook and therefore, has to accept that a draw by perpetual checks is inevitable. }
25... f3 26. Rc3
{ Pinning the unprotected h3-rook. Black has to bring new pieces to the attack. }
26... Ng6 27. Rfc1
{ White's counterattack on the queenside is already too late. Now Black just needs to close the 8th rank. }
27... Bf8
{ Black closes the back rank and wants to put the queen on g5, when Qxa8 is not coming with a check. }
