{ Black has gathered all the pieces to the kingside for the final assault. However, we need to see the whole board, ignoring the situation on the queenside would be a one-sided approach. }
28... Nxh3+ 29. gxh3
{ Now comes the big surprise! Concentrating only on the kingside would be rather narrow-minded... }
29... Qd8
{ Suddenly, Black goes for the a7-knight on the queenside. We need to look at the whole board! A nice sacrifice on the kingside can lead to a win of an unprotected piece on the other flank. Chess is very complex!   On  29...Qxh3?  30.Qg2  comes, parrying all the threats. }
30. Bd3
{ White has the idea of vacating the b5-square for the retreating knight. Now Black can attack already from the h3-c8 diagonal. }
30... Qd7 31. Qc2 Qxh3
{ ∆ ...Nh4 and White cannot get rid of the strong h3-queen anymore. } 32. Qg2
{ The only defense to drive back the enemy queen. Is it a good idea to exchange the queens? }
32... Qd7 { Exchanging queens is not an option for Black. } 33. Bb5
{ Forcing away the black queen from the vital h3-c8 diagonal.   33.Qc2  Qh3  is only a repetition of moves. Black has lost  the h3-c8 diagonal but can continue the old plan of harassing the a7-knight. }
33... Qc7 34. Qh3
{ It seems that everything is in order in White's position; the queen now controls the important h3-c8 diagonal. Black has to find counterplay, this time on the queenside. The queen can change flanks very quickly...   To understand the subtleties of the queen's maneuver, let's return to an earlier moment: @@StartFEN@@5bk1/Np4r1/3p2n1/PB1Pp2p/1P2Pp1q/5PpP/3Q4/4NRK1 b - - 0 29@@EndFEN@@  29...Qxh3  was not a good idea in view of  30.Qg2  , when the black queen must retreat  to h4 since the d7-square is not available. Now Black's pieces are not fast enough to generate counterplay with a quick ...h5-h4 or by occupying the c-file under good circumstances.  For instance, after  30...Qh4  31.Nd3  Qd8  32.Qh3  , White is taking over.   By comparison, thanks to the queen's dance we can now take on h3, as after @@StartFEN@@5bk1/Np1q2r1/3p2n1/P2Pp2p/1P2Pp2/3B1PpP/2Q5/4NRK1 b - - 0 31@@EndFEN@@  31...Qxh3  ,  32.Qg2  has lost its strength. Black is fast enough with  32...Qd7  ,  threatening ...h5-h4-h3.  If White tries to prevent that with  33.Bb5  Qc7  34.Qh3  Qc3  , Black is very active, with threats  like ...Qxb4 and a check on the g1-a7 diagonal as well, eying the lonely knight on a7. }
34... Qc3
{ Threatening a check on the g1-a7 diagonal and taking the a7-knight. } 35. Nc8
Qxb4
{ Black soon gets the third pawn for the piece; the position remains very complicated. }
