{ White has a double attack against the a8-rook and the d7-bishop. The black knights look furious on the kingside. Do we react to the queenside threats directly, or can we create a bigger one on the other flank? }
30... Nxg2
{ Black again ignores White's attack on the queenside and sacrifices the knight on g2. In this way, Black weakens White's defense on the kingside and vacates the h4-square for the queen. }
31. Nxd7
{ The strong d7-bishop is more important than the useless rook on a8. Are we taking the d7-knight back, or are we planning a more forceful attacking move?   In case of  31.Nxa8?  Qh4  comes with an irresistible attack.   31.Kxg2?  looks logical to eliminate the attacking knight. However, this allows Black to spare the wonderful bishop for the attack! Here  31...Bb5  wins outright; on  32.Nxa8  there follows  32...Qh4  with a mating attack. }
31... Qh4 { That's right, no one is bothering with the d7-knight! } 32. Kxg2
{ White is now two pieces up, and Black still doesn't bother with the hanging d7-knight. Black has to focus on the attack against the white king. }
32... Qh2+ 33. Kf3
{ White may think that the king on f3 is relatively safe. How can Black prove that this is far from the truth? Vacate the g3-square for the queen! }
33... Nh1
{ The knight on the edge of the board is usually very bad, here is a nice exception. Now White has to find the only defense. }
34. Nf6+
{ The king has to avoid the 7th rank because of the annoying check on c7. }
34... Kh8 { White has to protect the f2-knight. } 35. Qb6
{ Finally we make an easy move... } 35... Nxf2
{ And the same goes for White, who has to take the piece back. } 36. Qxf2 Qh1+
37. Ke2 Rh2
{ White still has a lot of pieces for the queen, but the king remains vulnerable and the position is very complicated. }
