24. Bxf3 { White allows the frightening advance of the f- and g-pawns. } 24...
g4 25. hxg4 hxg4 26. Bd1 { Bring the next piece into the battle! } 26... Qh4
27. Nb6
{ Now the a8-rook and the c8-bishop are hanging. How do we react to those threats? }
27... f3 { With a bigger threat on the kingside! } 28. Qd3
{ We need to eliminate the best defender; which is that? } 28... g3
{ It is obviously the knight being close to the king. } 29. Qxf3
{ White is happy to sacrifice the knight back because then the queen will be wonderful on f2. We need to find a strong zwischenzug! }
29... Rf7 { The queen is hanging and White has to find a beautiful defense! }
30. Nd3
{ Sacrificing the queen, but the a8-rook and the c8-bishop are still hanging. }
30... Qh2+
{ The black queen comes closer to the opponent's king with a check. } 31. Kf1
{ It seems that finally, we can take the queen. However, this would bring back the bishop to f3, where it can successfully protect the g2-pawn. We need another beautiful intermediate move. }
31... Bh3
{ Now it is difficult to defend the g2-pawn, but White can close the f-file in order to save the queen. }
32. Bf4
{ All the pieces are hanging around, but again we ignore that and bring a new piece to the battle. }
32... Bh6
{ What a wonderful move! There are pins everywhere and Black wants to keep the f-file open, threatening ...Bxf4. The position will be equal but after quite difficult moves for both players.   After  32...Bh6  33.gxh3  , White eliminates the dangerous bishop.  No one is interested, that the a8-rook is hanging all the time.  33...Bxf4  34.Re2  Qxh3+  35.Ke1  Bxc1=  ,  with a very complicated but objectively equal position. }
