{ Black has to open the g- and the h-files, but the natural @@StartFEN@@4qbk1/1p1b2r1/p2p1n2/P2Pp2p/2N1PpPn/2Q2P2/1P2BNP1/4BRK1 b - - 0 29@@EndFEN@@  29...hxg4  is met by  30.Nxg4  and the h4-knight is hanging. We usually sacrifice a piece on the weakest spot, but this time comes a big surprise. }
29... Nxf3+
{ A bold from the blue! Sacrificing the knight for the extremely well-defended f3-pawn is very rare in the tournament practice, nevertheless, its idea is clear. In this way, White cannot avoid the opening of the g- and h-files. }
30. gxf3 { Prepare the threats against the white king on the g-file! } 30...
Qg6
{ Keeping the e1-bishop and the f2-knight in a passive waiting position.   30...hxg4  looks very natural to open up the g- and h-files, but it only activates the knight  vacating the f2-square for the bishop and the rook. }
