{ White has already two dangerous passed pawns on the queenside, and the a2-g8 diagonal is opened. Black has executed the necessary ...g5-g4 breakthrough, but the white g4-pawn is well protected.  In case of the mass exchanges on g4, White can protect the g2-pawn with Rf2 and Bf1, and create a counterattack on the a2-g8 diagonal with a queen check. So how can we destroy White's kingside? }
28... Nxf3+
{ This sacrifice annihilates the defending g2-pawn, and vacates the h4-square for the queen. }
29. gxf3 { Put the queen to its best-attacking square! } 29... Qh4
{ Black is already threatening a perpetual check via ...Qg3+ and ...Qh4+, so White has to defend against it. }
30. Rfd1
{ Clearing the f1-square for the king, which has to leave the g-file as soon as possible. Do we have finally time to open the g-file? }
30... hxg4 { Yes, White has to find the only moves to hold the balance. } 31.
Qb3+
{ White improves the queen's position with this check and can protect the 3rd rank. Inserting the check on the a2-d8 diagonal forces Black to another sacrifice. }
31... d5 { Now the central pawn is taboo. } 32. fxg4
{ This is again the only move, the queen can defend from the 3rd rank. } 32...
Bxg4
{ Now finally the king can run away from the dangerous kingside, but Black can keep the pressure on the kingside.   32...Bxg4  33.Kf1  Qh2  34.Qxd5+   34.Ke1  is met by the cold-blooded  34...Be7!  with the idea of ...Bh4.  35.Qxd5  Kh7  transposes to the main line.  34...Kh7  ,  White has to find the only defense again!  35.Ke1  ,  preparing the defense by Bf1. Now it is Black's turn to find the difficult attacking move...  35...Be7  opening up the 8th rank for the a8-rook and threatening ...Bh4. Following  36.Qxe5  Bh4∞  ,  the position is objectively equal, but in a practical game, even strong grandmasters would suffer a lot to find the best moves! }
