{ White has material advantage and the very important light-squared bishop is hanging on c8. What should Black do? }
22... Nxe4
{ Opening up the h4-d8 diagonal and threatening ...Qh4. Black has to attack on the kingside, and the target is the h2-pawn because White's dark-squared bishop is missing.   Most players would play  22...Bd7  without thinking, and would be very surprised after the beautiful response  23.Nc6! }
23. Nxc8 Qh4
{ There is no big difference in comparison to the 23.Rxc8 variation, which we will check next. The motifs are the same. }
24. h3 { Black has to prepare the sacrifice on h3. } 24... Ng5 { ∆ ...Nxh3 }
25. Kg1 Nxh3+ 26. gxh3 Qxh3 27. Rf2
{ This is the only way to avoid the quick mate. Do we take now the rook? }
27... Nh4 { Not at all, we do not want to allow the knight to come for help. }
28. Bf1
{ Now White forces Black to take on f3, but the g-file is already opened. }
28... gxf2+ 29. Kxf2 Qg3+ 30. Ke2 Nxf3 { Black's attack crashes through. } *

