{ White has an extra pawn on the queenside, and the one on b5 is also hanging. Black has to find the target on the kingside, but the regular ones, g2, and h2 are well-defended. So what's next? }
27... Nxe4
{ Black wants to deflect the f3-pawn in order to push the f4-pawn with great effect. }
28. Bxb5
{ White has to continue the harvest on the queenside. Black doesn't want to exchange the attacking light-squared bishop and has to create a strong threat with it. }
28... Bg4
{ There are some other strong moves but in this case, we always go for the most beautiful one! }
29. Bf1
{ Protecting the important g2-pawn. Now the g2 and f3-pawns are well-protected, where is our new target?   Accepting the sacrifice with  29.fxg4  allows finally the devastating advance  of the f4-pawn:  29...f3-+  .   29.Qf1  runs into a fork motif after  29...Bxf3  30.gxf3  g2  , winning the queen outright. }
29... gxh2 { Opening up the h-file. } 30. Kxh2
{ The bishop cannot take the pawn back, because  30.Bxh2?  runs into  30...Nf2+  , which wins the queen.   Black has to bring the queen to h4, which would even be mate in this position. How can Black force matters since the h4-knight is merely an obstacle now? }
30... Nxf3+
{ Ruining White's defense and winning a vital tempo to reach the h4-square with the queen. }
31. gxf3 Qe7 *

