{ White is clearly winning on the queenside, but the king is very vulnerable. If Black can get rid of the f6-knight, ...Qh4 may come with nasty mating threats. However, in this case, the d7-bishop falls, and the white bishop may come back to the defense via Bxd7-h3. So what do you reckon?  (Sedrakian-Bragin, SU 1989) }
23... Nxe4
{ Black opens up the h4-d8 diagonal for the queen, and the knight can be very effective from g5 against an h3-bishop. }
24. fxe4 Qh4 { ∆ ...Qh2# } 25. Rf3
