{ White is so far not so successful in getting a real advantage on the queenside. Black has already sacrificed the bishop for two pawns on the kingside, and the white king is in trouble. A lot of white pieces defend passively on the first rank, but Black has to come out with the next breakthrough. }
25... Nxe4
{ Black wants to deflect the f3-pawn in order to create two mighty connected pawns on the third rank. }
26. Ng2
{ Koutsin-Frolov, Kyiv 1995. White wants to exchange Black's dangerous attacking pieces. It seems that White's strategy works very well, and there is no way to avoid further exchanges.   26.fxe4?  allows Black to connect the beautiful pawns after  26...f3!-+  . }
26... Nxf3+
{ What a big surprise! Instead of the sad exchanges, Black sacrifices the second piece and even exchanges the queen! }
27. Bxf3 Qxh1+ 28. Kxh1 Nf2+ 29. Kg1
{ If White wants to find some relief, and gives back some material via  29.Rxf2  gxf2  30.Rf1  , then after  30...Rxa4  , we can start calculating the pawns, and Black has a lot of them. }
29... e4
{ As we can see, Black has four strong connected passed pawns for the sacrificed pieces, so materially the situation is not that bad. Two white pieces are hanging, so soon Black gets back some material. }
30. Ra3
{ Sacrificing back the bishop, but establishing a blockade on the f3-square. }
30... exf3 31. Rxf3 Rxa4
{ Now Black has already four pawns for the sacrificed piece, so Black should be slightly better. }
