[SetUp "1"]

{ The white queen has penetrated to a7, and the threat is Bxb6, deflecting the black queen from the h4-d8 diagonal. On the kingside the black pawns are advancing as the forest of Birnam, but how can we bring our queen into the attack? }
23... Nxe4
{ This knight sacrifice ruins White's defensive pawn structure and gives rise to a quick ...Qg5. }
24. Bxb6 Qg5
{ This was the main idea, opening up the h4-d8 diagonal for the queen. } 25.
fxe4
{ Black can push three pawns on the kingside, but the choice is fairly easy. }
25... f3
{ Attacking the bishop and the g2-pawn, opening the f-file and the c1-h6 diagonal, and creating a nice square on f4 for the knight. Not bad from a modest pawn move. }
26. Qa2
{ The passive retreat  26.Bd1?  is severely punished by  26...Qd2-+  . We can take  the e2-bishop, or we can bring a new piece into the battle. Be alert! }
26... Nf4
{ 26...fxe2?  allows the white queen to come back for the defense with  27.Qxe2±  . }
27. Nxf4
{ Black can take back on f4 three ways, but only one capture is good. } 27...
exf4
{ Opening up the long diagonal, especially the e5-square for the bishop, and creating another annoying f-pawn. }
28. Bxf3
{ White sacrifices back the bishop.   28.Bd1  is a passive retreat, allowing Black to continue the attack by advancing the kingside pawns:  28...fxg2  29.Kxg2  Be5  with compensation.  The bishop is ideally posted in the center, preparing the ...f4-f3 push. }
28... gxf3 29. Kh1
{ 29.Rxf3  is strongly met by  29...Bg4  , attacking the blockading piece. }
29... fxg2+ 30. Qxg2
{ Black certainly wants to avoid the exchange of queens and wants to emphasize the pressure on the light squares. }
30... Qh5
{ We have an extremely complicated position with equal chances.   After  31.Rg1  Rf7  32.Nxd6  ,  it seems that too many black pieces are hanging around, there is no defense, but think about the counterattack!  32...h3  ,  the queen is attacked and cannot leave the f3-square unprotected.  33.Qf1  and now comes Black's counterattack on the light squares.  Following  33...Bg4  34.Rxg4  ,  White has to liquidate to an endgame, making the king a bit safer.  34...Qxg4  35.Nxf7  Kxf7∞  ,  White has three connected passed pawns in the center, but the king is still very vulnerable. The position is objectively equal. }
