{ White is already two pawns up, and the strong g4-knight has to be exchanged, otherwise, Black cannot get close to the white king. We can take it with the bishop or knight. Which is the preferable one, and why? }
28... Nxg4
{ 28...Bxg4?  29.hxg4  Nxg4  is strongly met by the typical defensive move  30.Qh3! }
29. Bxg4
{ 29.hxg4  can be answered by  29...Qg5  or  29...Bd7  , with good compensation in both cases. }
29... Bxg4 30. hxg4
{ The natural reply is just taking back on g4. However, it is better to search for candidate moves instead of automatically going for the material. As usual, we would like to open up the g-file against the white king. How can we do that this time? }
30... Nxg2
{ Black wants to avoid the exchange of the h4-knight for the bishop and sacrifices it for a pawn! Opening up the g-file is one of the main motifs in this King's Indian structure.   30...Rxg4  allows the well-known defense  31.Qh3  , while @@StartFEN@@3q1bk1/1p4r1/3p4/PN1Pp3/4PpPn/1Q6/1P4P1/4BRK1 b - - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  30...Qd7  allows White to eliminate the dangerous attacker with  31.Bxh4  . }
31. Kxg2
{ 31...Rxg4  would be the most natural reply, but we do not want to take  the g4-pawn with the rook. We would like to take with the queen, so let's prepare ...Qxg4! }
31... Qd7 32. Kf2
{ 32.Qf3  loses  the b5-knight.  32...Qxb5  comes, with nice compensation for the pawn. }
32... Qxg4
{ Black is ready to give checks and has got good compensation for the sacrificed piece! }
