[FEN "r3qbk1/NpRb2r1/1B1p1nn1/P2Pp3/4Pppp/1Q1N1P2/1P2B1PP/5R1K b - - 0 24"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ White is much better on the queenside, as a pawn was already won and the one on b7 is hanging as well. On the other hand, most of White's pieces are far away from the kingside, and the black pawns look frightening on the fourth rank. How do we open up the position against the white king? }
24... h3 { Black now destroys White's defensive wall of pawns. } 25. g3
{ White has to avoid the opening of the h-file. It seems that White has avoided the opening of the position on the kingside. The g3-pawn restricts the g6 knight's possibilities. Is it really true?! }
25... fxg3 26. hxg3
{ Now comes the typical sacrifice in these types of positions in order to open files and diagonals on the kingside and free the path of the g4-pawn. }
26... Nf4
{ The knight was really restricted, so Black simply sacrifices it, deflecting the g3-pawn. }
27. gxf4 { Two connected passed pawns on the 3rd rank are fantastic! } 27... g3
28. Rg1 { It is time to come with the remaining pieces. } 28... Qh5
{ ∆ ... Qh4, ...g2, and ...Qg3. } 29. Nc6
{ This is a wonderful motif, bringing back the knight from the edge of the board over the minefield. The knight is taboo:  29...bxc6?  loses to  30.dxc6  with a discovered check. Black has to continue the attacking plan on the kingside. }
29... Qh4 { ∆  30.--  g2  31.Kh2  Qg3  . } 30. Bf2
{ White sacrifices back a piece. Do we take the bishop? } 30... h2
{ Certainly not, we create bigger threats on the kingside and White has to give up material in order to avoid the immediate collapse of the position.   White has to sacrifice back the material with  31.Rxg3  , but now the g-file opens up.  31...Rxg3  32.Bxg3  Qxg3  33.Qb6  bxc6-+  and finally it is Black who has the extra piece. }
*

