[SetUp "1"]

24. Qe1
{ Fighting against ...g3 and ...Qh4, but allowing something else in return. }
24... Ne3 25. Nxc7
{ The e3-knight is more important than the f1-rook.   On  25.Rg1  Qg5-+  comes with  the nasty threat of ...g3. Do we take the rook or continue our attacking plan? }
25... Qg5 { Targeting the weakness on g2. } 26. Bb6
{ White wants to get rid of the annoying knight on e3. The main target is the same, the g2-pawn. How can we attack it with more pieces? }
26... Nh4 27. Bxe3
{ White finally exchanges the marvelous knight on e3, and in case of the natural take back  27...fxe3  28.fxg4  may save the day. An attacker always has to think about zwischenzugs! }
27... Nxg2
{ Instead of recapturing on e3, Black sacrifices the other knight as well! In this way, Black opens up the important g-file. }
28. Qf2
{ 28.Kxg2  runs into a nice mating attack after  28...gxf3  29.Kxf3  Bh3! }
28... Nxe3 29. Rg1
{ Black has won the material back and is a pawn up with a tremendous attack. We only need a consolidating move leaving the g-file with our king. }
29... Kh7
{ Black has an easy win, the e3-knight and the pair of bishops decide the battle. }
