{ White has just executed the typical breakthrough on the queenside by c4-c5, and Bxa5 is threatened; the target is the c7 pawn. On the other flank, the black pawn reached the g3-square, so ...Qh4 would be a decisive blow. However, the g3-pawn is also hanging, and the f6-knight blocks the queen on the h4-d8 diagonal. How do we solve this problem? }
22... Nxd5
{ Black sacrifices the knight on d5, taking an important pawn. We have two threats now: ...Qh4 and ...Ne3. }
23. Qc4 { Pinning the knight, but Black continues the attack. } 23... Qh4 24.
Qxd5+ Kh7 25. hxg3 { 25.h3  is certainly answered by  25...Bxh3!-+  . } 25...
fxg3 26. Bxg3
{ White has to sacrifice the piece back, otherwise, the mate is inevitable. }
26... Qxg3 27. Ra3
{ 27.Qxa8?  is too greedy,  27...Bh3  comes with a double threat: mate or winning the queen. Now Black has to find a new target; remember, unprotected pieces... }
27... Ba6 { There are too many white pieces on the f1-a6 diagonal. } *

