[SetUp "1"]

{ Black has executed the evergreen push ...g4-g3 but cannot take back on g3 because of Qg5 and the pawn falls. However, the g3-pawn is usually more important than a piece... }
23... Nxd5
{ Black sacrifices the knight in order to open up the h4-d8 diagonal and take away the g5-square from the enemy queen.   Now on  24.cxd5?  fxg3  with the idea of ...Qh4 is possible. }
24. g4
{ White has to build up a stronghold on the kingside avoiding the quick opening of the position. However, White also has to pay a heavy price for that. }
24... Ne3
{ The knight has got an excellent square here. The rook has to leave the f1-square, but it is very difficult to see the differences between the rook moves. }
25. Ra1
{ The rook can organize some counterattack on the a-file.  Sometimes even in attacking positions, we need to make defensive moves. So we need to fight against c4-c5 and open the 7th rank for the rook for later operations. }
25... Bf8
{ Unfortunately,  25...h5  is less effective now because of the nice counterattack on the queenside.  26.Bxc7!  Rxc7  27.Nxc7  Qxc7  28.gxh5  and the black queen is far away from the kingside. }
26. Nxc7
{ White has to deflect the black pieces from the kingside attack.  26.Bxc7?  is less effective now because after  26...Rxc7  27.Nxc7  Qxc7  ,  the h5-pawn is not hanging. }
26... Rxc7
{ Here comes the big difference: White can also use tactical motifs! } 27. Nb4
{ This is a cold-blooded move improving the knight's position. } 27... Bb7
{ Controlling the vital d5-square. } 28. Bxc7 Qxc7
{ Materially, Black is a little bit better, but the whole fight is ahead of us. }
*

