[SetUp "1"]

25. Rc1
{ At first sight, this looks logical, protecting the c4-pawn and just in case preparing the push c4-c5. Black now has to open up the files on the kingside at any cost. }
25... h5 26. c5
{ White ignores the threat on the kingside and continues the advance on the other flank. }
26... hxg4 27. fxg4
{ Black has to open up the g-file and eliminate the g-pawn, but which one?! }
27... Nxg2
{ It is better to sacrifice the knight and get the best defender, the g2-pawn. }
28. Nxd6
{ White also ignores the threat and attacks on the queenside.  26.cxd6  with the similar idea founders on  26...f3!  and Black comes first.  The f7-rook and the g2-knight are hanging. Do we ignore this again? }
28... Qh4
{ Yes and yes! Bringing the queen into the battle as quick as possible is the best solution. }
29. Nxf7 { Now we need to create real mating threats. } 29... Qg3
{ ∆ ...Ne3 and ...Qg2 mate. } 30. Kh1 Ne3 31. Ne1 { Defending the g2-square. }
31... Qh3+ 32. Kg1 { Finally, we have time to deal with the hanging pieces. }
32... Kxf7 { White has the extra exchange, but the king is exposed. } *

