[SetUp "1"]

{ White didn't do much on the queenside; the c7-pawn is hanging, but that's all. Black's pawn is already on g3 and the bishop sacrifice on h3 is hanging in the air.  The typical plan is to bring the black queen to h4, but what can we do with the f6-knight? In fact, the position is not so typical, the tactical motif is extraordinary! Reinderman-Golod, VAM Hoogeveen op 1998. }
24... Nxd5
{ We may think, that this move is a prelude to ...Qh4 and ...Bxh3, but now comes the big surprise. }
25. exd5
{ 25.cxd5  allows the simple  25...Bxb5  , winning the pawn. The next move is simply wonderful, look at the whole board, not only the kingside. Open up the diagonal  of the g7-bishop! }
25... e4
{ Black executes the breakthrough in the center. The d3-knight is attacked, but the real target is the a7-rook since after ...Bxb5, ...Bd4+ wins it! }
26. Bc3
{ White is ready to give back the piece but wants to neutralize the fianchettoed bishop. }
26... Bxc3 27. Nxc3
{ We can certainly take the knight on d3, but think of the unprotected pieces in White's camp. }
27... Qf6
{ Three white pieces are attacked, but the big threat is again a check on d4 and taking the undefended rook on a7. }
28. Ra3 { White protects two pieces from the three. } 28... exd3
{ Finally, we take the hanging knight on d3. } 29. Qxd3
{ The position is materially equal, but the black pieces dominate the board. Let's activate all of them! }
29... Bf5
{ Black's pieces are way better than White's.   29...Bf5  30.Qd2  Re7  ∆ ...Re3 with a total control over the dark squares.  31.Rea1  ,  White leaves the pin on the e-file. Following  31...Re3-+  ,  all the black pieces stand better than their colleagues. }
*

