[SetUp "1"]

26. Nc1
{ White keeps the extra piece, but the passive retreat of the knight gives rise to Black's typical attack on the kingside. }
26... Qh4
{ Now Black will continue the well-known attack against the weakness on h3. }
27. Ra2
{ The rook leaves the lethal a7-square and wants to defend from the 2nd rank. Black has to put more pressure on the f3-pawn. }
27... Ne5
{ Now comes the 2nd wave of the attack, as the white light pieces except the e2-bishop are far away from their monarch. }
28. Bc3
{ 28.fxe4  allows the final breakthrough by  28...f3-+  . It is already too late to bring back the pieces for the defense. The time has come for the final assault. How do we break White's defensive pawn formation? }
28... Bxh3 29. gxh3 Qxh3 30. Bf1
{ It may seem that Black's attack has been repelled, the queen has to leave, and the 2nd rank is protected by the a2-rook. Where is our next target? }
30... Qh5 { The f3-pawn cannot be protected anymore. } 31. Bxe5
{ Remember, the attacker has to think about beautiful intermediate moves all the time! }
31... exf3
{ Ignoring the piece but creating a lethal pawn formation on the 3rd rank. }
32. Bd4
{ White now has three extra pieces, but the connected pawns on the 3rd rank continue their advance. }
32... f2+ 33. Rxf2
{ White has to sacrifice back a whole rook, otherwise, a mate comes on h2. }
33... gxf2+ 34. Bxf2
{ White still has a big material advantage, but there remained one dangerous black pawn on the kingside. }
34... f3 { With a lethal threat of ...Be5 and ...Rg7+. } *

