26. Ra2
{ White is happy to give back the piece since the rook has left the undermined a7-square. Do we take simply the d3-knight, or do we eliminate the defender of the vital d4-square and continue the attack? }
26... Rxb5
{ Instead of taking the knight, we sacrifice our rook and later a bishop! By eliminating the b5-knight, Black takes control over the important d4-square. The d7-bishop is more valuable than the rook because we want to sacrifice it on h3. }
27. cxb5 Bd4+ 28. Kf1
{ The king wants to leave the dangerous kingside, but White's own pieces are in the way. Black can follow the well-trodden path of sacrifices. }
28... Bxh3 29. fxe4
{ 29.gxh3  founders on  29...Qd7  and there is no defense  against ...Qxh3. Now, if White has time for Bf3 and Ke2, the king will reach the safe haven. We cannot allow that! }
29... Bxg2+ { Chasing the king towards the black pieces. } 30. Kxg2 Nh4+ 31.
Kh3 { Black can finish the game in style not bothering with the h4-knight. }
31... f3 { The king on h3 soon gets mated. } *

