{ The white knight has penetrated the dream square of c7, attacking the a8-rook. At any moment it can also close the c8-bishop's diagonal by Ne6. On the other hand, Black has also a big threat of ...gxh3 opening up the g-file. }
26... Nxd5
{ 26...gxh3  27.Nxa8  was also possible, but the beautiful text move wants to improve this variation. By sacrificing the knight, Black opens up the diagonal of the queen to  g5  , which will be important in some lines. }
27. exd5
{ We sacrificed the knight and the rook is still hanging. What's next? } 27...
gxh3 { Black opens the g-file, ignoring the threat of Nxa8. } 28. Bd3
{ Surprisingly enough, this is the only move, very difficult to find in a practical game. After  28.Nxh3  , Black can get a material advantage without any problems with  28...Bxh3  29.Rf2  Bf5  . }
28... e4
{ 28...Rxg2  29.Kh1  Qg5  30.Ne4  Qg8  31.Nf6  Qg5  32.Nh7  Qg8  33.Nf6  may lead to a funny repetition of moves and the simple @@StartFEN@@r1bq1b1k/2N3r1/3p3n/p2Pp2p/P4p2/2RB1P1p/2Q2NP1/4BRK1 b - - 1 28@@EndFEN@@  28...Rb8  is also a valid alternative. Again and again, we go for the most exciting variations. }
29. Nxe4
{ Do not underestimate the resources of the defense! In many cases, White sacrifices a queen to avoid the mating attack.  29.Bb5  gives a free hand for Black on the kingside and in the center after  29...Rxg2  30.Kh1  e3  . }
29... Rxg2+ 30. Kh1 Rxc2 31. Rxc2 Rb8
{ A very complicated position has arisen. White has a rook and a knight for the queen, but this time the white pieces are very active. White has enough compensation for the queen, but no more than that. }
