{ Black has created a nice battery on the h-file attacking the h2-pawn. However, it seems that the g1-bishop is enough to defend the weakness, as it is hard to find a light piece to attack it. On the other hand, we can find some nice mating motifs! }
20... Nfxd5
{ Black wants to deflect the e4-pawn to clear the way for the other knight to f5 and threaten ...Ng3 mate. }
21. Qd2
{ Running out of a possible ...Ne3 attack. The d5-knight is hanging, but we desperately want to continue our attack on the kingside. }
21... g4
{ This is a very nice idea.  21...Ne3  is met by  22.Nb6  counterattacking the rook. }
22. Nf2 { The knight is coming back to defense; its ideal position is on g4. }
22... g3
{ Finally, the g-pawn has reached the 3rd rank. White now has to secure the g4-square for the knight. }
23. Rxc8+ { Eliminating the dangerous light-squared bishop. } 23... Rxc8 24.
Ng4 { The knight is wonderful here. } 24... Ne3
{ The black knight also arrives at the desired square. } 25. Nxh6+ Bxh6
{ Black has the more active pieces and a not very important extra pawn. } *

