21. exd5 { White runs into Black's main plan. } 21... Nf5
{ The e7-knight comes with great effect on f5. } 22. Rxc8+
{ White has to eliminate the dangerous sniper on c8, otherwise, ...Bxh3 comes, ruining White's kingside. }
22... Rxc8 23. h3
{ Here we cannot sacrifice on h3, so we need to find a new target. } 23... Ng3+
24. Kh2
{ The more valuable piece is the knight on g3 and not the rook on f1, so taking it is out of the question here. How can we open up the kingside? }
24... e4
{ Here is the typical central breakthrough again, using the pin on the d1-h5 diagonal.  25.fxe4  loses to  25...Nxe2  . }
25. Nf2
{ The knight is a very good defender, controlling the h3 and g4-squares. Black has a choice between taking the rook or the bishop. What is your opinion? }
25... Nxe2
{ 25...Nxf1  was also good, but Black wants to keep the initiative on both flanks. }
26. Qxe2 exf3
{ Surprisingly enough, Black is not against the exchange of queens because the white pieces lack any coordination. }
27. Qxf3 Qxf3 28. gxf3
{ Now the rook on the c-file is very active, and the a4-knight is out of play. }
28... Rc2
{ White has two knights against a rook and a pawn, but the second pawn will be lost, and the pin on the 2nd rank is annoying. }
