23. g4 { The white king has more air now. How should Black proceed? } 23...
fxg3 24. exd5
{ Now ...Nf5 is not a mating threat anymore. Black has to find a new target. }
24... Ng6 { ∆ ...Bh3 and ...Nf4, exploiting the weakness of g2. } 25. f4
{ Opening the d1-h5 diagonal and attacking the queen. However, this push creates even more weaknesses on the kingside. }
25... Qh3 26. fxg5 { The target is the same, we need to attack the g2-square. }
26... Nh4
{ Black ignores the hanging rook and creates a mate in two threat with ...g2+. }
27. Bf3
{ Defending against ...g2+, but leaving the f1-rook unprotected. Black can certainly take the rook on f1 but is obsessed with the mating attack! }
27... gxh2
{ Opening up the files and instead of taking a rook, sacrificing one on h6! }
28. gxh6
{ A lot of pieces are hanging around, but a real King's Indian player cannot be greedy... }
28... Bxh6
{ Simply taking back the pawn while the f1-rook and the g1-bishop are still hanging.   29.Bg2  defends the rook, but now the bishop falls and the h-file will also be opened.  29...hxg1=Q+  30.Kxg1  ,  let's attack with our remaining pieces!  30...Be3+  31.Rf2  Qg3  ,  Black still doesn't take anything but creates a lot of nasty pins.  32.Rcf7  Bf5  ,  closing the f-file and threatening to take the rook again.  33.Qe2  and now comes something unbelievable: Black is a whole rook down and plays a 'quiet' move! After  33...Bd4-+  ,  White cannot improve the position and has to wait for the last blow of ...Rg8. }
*

