{ The c8-bishop is one of the most important attacking pieces in this variation of the King's Indian. It seems that Black cannot avoid the exchange of it. If we have to say goodbye, let's do it in an extraordinary way! }
22... Bf5
{ What a surprise! The bishop sacrifices itself on an unusual square but helps the e7-knight to get into the battle. }
23. Nc4
{ The b6-knight couldn't take the bishop, so it comes back now attacking the weakness on d6. Nxd6 is a real threat, but we do not want to lose precious time with a passive defense of that pawn. }
23... Nfxd5
{ Now already two light pieces are hanging, but the d6-pawn is safe... } 24.
exd5
{ 24.exf5  is met by  24...Nxf5  followed  by ...h4-h3, opening up the lines against the white king. Now we need to improve our rook's position. }
24... Rg6 { The white king is in a clear and present danger. } *

