[FEN "5rrk/1pN3bp/1B1p2n1/P3q1n1/2B1ppP1/8/1P4PP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 0 28"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ The g8-rook is hanging, but Black has two dangerous connected pawns in the center. If we divide the board into two parts, we can see that all the white pieces but the f1-rook are on the queenside, far away from the king. How do we start our offensive on the kingside? }
28... f3
{ Black wants to weaken White's kingside. The f-file can be open, the g2-pawn is the real target. }
29. Bxg8
{ Do we take back the bishop or create a bigger threat on the kingside targeting the weak g2-pawn? }
29... Nh4
{ 29...Rxg8  was played in the game Kiriakov-Zimmerman, Sochi 2004.  The g8-bishop doesn't bother us at all, we focus on our attack against the white king. }
30. Rf2 { Defending the 2nd rank. But Black will open up the f-file. } 30...
fxg2 { ∆ ...Nh3# } 31. Rxg2
{ White has to sacrifice an exchange back in order to take the dangerous g2-pawn. }
31... Nxg2 32. Kxg2 { Now comes the final blow. } 32... e3
{ Threatening ...Rf2+ and ...Qe4+. White can resign. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) The ...f4-f3 push"]
[Black "Diagram 5A"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "5rrk/1pN3bp/1B1p2n1/P3q1n1/2B1p1P1/5p2/1P4PP/R2Q1RK1 w - - 0 29"]
[SetUp "1"]

29. gxf3 { This only helps Black to bring new pieces into the attack. } 29...
Nxf3+ 30. Rxf3 { Otherwise, mate is coming. } 30... exf3 31. Bxg8
{ Now our target is the h2-pawn; let's prepare the battery on the h2-b8 diagonal! }
31... Qf4
{ Threatening ...Be5, which creates a strong battery on the h2-e5 diagonal, and ...f2+. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) The ...f4-f3 push"]
[Black "Diagram 5B"]
[Result "*"]
