[SetUp "1"]

30. Bd5
{ White wants to save the bishop and is now a whole rook up. However, the g2-pawn is a notorious target. How can we create beautiful mating threats using the weakness of g2? }
30... Qxb2
{ Threatening ...Qxg2 mate, but it seems that White has a simple defense. } 31.
Rf2 { Now comes the big surprise, just open the f-file! } 31... fxg2
{ A bold from the blue! On  32.Rxb2  follows  32...Nh3  mate! } 32. Rxf8+ Bxf8
33. Bd4+ Bg7 34. Bxb2 { Now comes the beautiful knight mate! } 34... Nh3#
{ Just another version of the same mate. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12) Ideas connected to ...gxf3 and ...gxh3"]
[Black "Diagram 1"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b1qnk1/ppp3rp/3b1n2/PNNPp3/1P2PppB/5P2/4B1PP/R3QRK1 b - - 0 22"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Black usually attacks with ...g3, but here it is not possible. Taking on f3 is usually answered by gxf3, but here the pin on the g-file forces White to take back with the piece. }
22... gxf3
{ 22...Qh5?  looks tricky because on  23.Bxf6?  g3!  creates well-known mating threats. The problem is that after  23.fxg4  Nxg4  24.h3  , the knight is pinned and Black is lost.   22...Qg6  allows  23.Bxf6  , and although we have the zwischenzug  23...gxf3  , after  24.Bxf3  Qxf6  , White's  blockade is effective on the f3-square. }
23. Rxf3
{ In most of the cases, the rook is a bad blockader, here it wants to defend the 3rd rank. The knight is hanging on f6 and the e3-square is weak; let's make a profit from that! }
23... Ng4
{ Continuing the attack with  23...Qg6  is also good.  24.Bf1  a6  , preventing any queenside expansion that White might have with a  future a6.   Instead,  24...Bxc5  25.bxc5  Nxe4  allows White to restore the dynamic balance with  26.a6  bxa6  27.Nc3  , when the game remains unclear.  25.Na3  h6  ,  Black will be able to bring the remaining pieces into the game smoothly, with ...N8h7, ...Bg4, ...Kh8, and ...Rag8 ideas. }
24. Raa3 { Here is the total defense of the 3rd rank. } 24... Ng6
{ Forcing back the active dark-squared bishop. } 25. Bf2
{ The f2-bishop is good for the attack and for the defense, so we get rid of it. }
25... Nxf2 26. Rxf2 Kh8
{ Anticipating the jump of the knight to e6, we have to take on e6 and then the a2-g8 diagonal will be open, therefore the king has to leave it. Later, ...Nh4 and ...Bf8 may come. Black has strong pressure on the semi-opened g-file and on the dark squares. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12) Ideas connected to ...gxf3 and ...gxh3"]
[Black "Diagram 1A"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b1qnk1/ppp3rp/3b1n2/PNNPp3/1P2Pp1B/5p2/4B1PP/R3QRK1 w - - 0 23"]
[SetUp "1"]

23. Bxf3
{ White leaves the b5-knight unprotected. Should we take it or look for something else? }
23... Ng4
{ 23...Qxb5  is not a good exchange of the knights. After  24.Bxf6  , White remains with two defender bishops. }
24. Qe2
{ Protecting the knight on b5, but now the h4-bishop remains without a defense. }
24... Qh5 25. h3
{ White is counterattacking the g4-knight, but at the end, the g-pawn will be lost giving Black excellent attacking chances on the g- and h-files.   25.g3  doesn't help because of  25...Ng6  . }
25... Qxh4 26. Bxg4 Bxg4 27. hxg4
{ Black usually concentrates on the kingside, sometimes forgetting about the other flank. We need to focus on the whole board! }
27... a6
{ Forcing the active b5-knight to retreat or to take the passive dark-squared bishop. That being said, the direct  27...h5  with the idea  28.gxh5  Nh7  followed by  ...Nf6-g4 works as well. Black is spoiled for choice already. }
28. Nxd6 cxd6 29. Ne6 Rxg4 { With a winning attack on the g- and h-files. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12) Ideas connected to ...gxf3 and ...gxh3"]
[Black "Diagram 2"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b2n1k/1p2q1r1/p2p1n2/P2Pp2p/NPB1PppB/5P2/6PP/2RQ1R1K b - - 0 26"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ In most of the King's Indian combinations, the fireworks begin with ...g4-g3. However, Black has other attacking options as well... }
26... gxf3 { Opening up the g-file and the h3-c8 diagonal. } 27. gxf3
{ Now the bishop comes with tempo to the battle. } 27... Bh3 28. Rg1
{ In most cases, this is the problem with the ...gxf3 plan. If the white rook comes to g1, it is difficult to continue the attack. This position is however a nice exception. Note the unprotected h4-bishop and the mating threat... }
28... Nxe4
{ This is the point, as  29.Bxe7??  runs into a mate in one after  29...Nf2  . }
29. Qc2
{ White wants to exchange the e4-knight for the h4-bishop, taking back with the queen. }
29... Qxh4 30. Qxe4 { Now comes the penetration to the 2nd rank. } 30... Qf2
{ Black has got a serious threat: ...Bg2+ with mate on the next move. } 31.
Rxg7 Kxg7 32. Rg1+
{ We need a brave move with our king just as Steinitz advocated many-many years ago. }
32... Kf6
{ ∆ ...Bf5, breaking the blockade of the e4-square.   After  33.Nb6  ,  we have no time to leave with the rook because of Bd3, so again comes an intermediate move.  33...Bf5  34.Qe2  Qxe2  35.Bxe2  Rd8-+  .  Black has an extra pawn, better pawn structure, and more active pieces. }
*

