[SetUp "1"]

{ The white knight has penetrated to c7, attacking the a8-rook and also planning Ne6, closing the c8-bishop's diagonal. Which is the bigger threat? Duemig-Balcerak, RL-op 1993. }
22... gxh3
{ The a8-rook is less important than the opening of the g-file; now the g2-pawn falls.   22...gxf3  allows White to defend  the g2-pawn with  23.Bxf3  , when Black's advantage just suffered a downgrade. }
23. Nxa8 Rxg2+ 24. Kh1
{ The king looks safer here, the h-pawn may give to it a shelter. The c8-bishop is threatened and the f2-knight is hanging as well. Do these things bother us or do we just continue our attacking plan and try to bring the queen to the battle? }
24... Nh7
{ These don't bother us, not at all! Our threat of ...Qg5 followed by ...Rh2 and ...Qg2 mate is just bigger!   24...Nd7  with the same ...Qg5 idea,  or  24...Qe8  followed by  ...Qg6 put White in a hard spot too. }
25. Be1
{ White wants to close the g-file with the knight and take the h4-knight with the bishop.   25.Rxc8  simply helps the black queen to find the  25...Qg5  move. }
25... Qg5 { ∆ ...Rh2+ and ...Qg2#. } 26. Ng4
{ White has to give back the knight to avoid mate. } 26... hxg4
{ Black is ready for the second wave of the attack. } *

