23. Bf1
{ White wants to avoid ...Rxg2+, but the pawn will fall in another way. } 23...
hxg2 24. Nxa8 gxf1=Q+ 25. Kxf1
{ The king wants to leave the kingside, but the next weakness, the f3-pawn, cannot be well-defended. First, we have to secure the light-squared bishop. }
25... Bd7 26. Nc7
{ Otherwise, the knight falls. Let's attack the weak pawn in White's position! }
26... Rg3 27. Rc3
{ There is no other defense. Now we need to bring the queen into the battle. Sometimes we take a retreating move into account. }
27... Ne8 28. Ne6
{ At first sight, it seems that White can hold, as the e6-knight is usually very strong. We focus on the kingside in most cases. This time the queen will be activated on the other flank. }
28... Qa5 { Black prepares a lethal check on the f1-a6 diagonal. } 29. Rd3 Qb5
{ Pinning the d3-rook, after which the f3-pawn will fall. } *

