{ The white knight has penetrated to c7, attacking the a8-rook and threatening to jump on the vital e6-square. If the latter happens, the h3-pawn can be better defended. Black is now at a crossroads. }
23... gxh3
{ Black continues the attack on the kingside, sacrificing the a8-rook but opening up the g-file. }
24. Nxa8 Rxg2+ 25. Kh1
{ The black queen belongs on g5, creating the well-known mating motif ...Rh2+ and ...Qg2 mate. The f6-knight has to leave but in the most forced way. }
25... Nh5
{ ∆ ...Ng3#  and ...Qg5, so White has no other option than taking the h5-knight. }
26. Bxh5 { Now the black queen reaches the desired square. } 26... Qg5
{ ∆ ...Rh2+ and ...Qg2 mate. } *

