35. Qf1
{ Offering the exchange of queens and protecting the f2-rook. Should we accept it? }
35... Qf3
{ Certainly, Black has to avoid the exchange of the attacking queen. } 36. Bh6
{ Clearing the way to d2 for the king. It wants to leave the pin at the expense of sacrificing back a whole rook. Now the last remaining piece joins the attack. }
36... Nf4
{ The black pieces dominate the whole board. Quality here defeats quantity. }
37. Kd2 Bxf2 { Black is only an exchange down. } 38. Bxf4 exf4
{ We need the strong passed pawn on the f-file, as after  38...Qxf4  39.Kc2  Qxe4  Qd3  , Black's bishops are still strong but we cannot say the same about the e-pawn, which can now be stopped in its tracks. }
39. Kc2
{ Here comes a rather difficult move because we usually start our analysis with checks. }
39... Qe3
{ It is a 'quiet' move with big threats like ...Be2 or ...Bf3.   However, the bishop pair combined with the passed f4-pawn and the out-of-play knight on a8 yields Black additional options in  39...Qxe4+  40.Qd3  Bf5  , or @@StartFEN@@N5k1/pp6/3p4/P2P4/4Ppb1/5q2/1PK2b2/2R2Q2 b - - 0 39@@EndFEN@@  39...Be3  directly, liquidating into a winning endgame for us. }
