{ White just took on d6, creating the big threat of a fork by dxc7. On the other hand, Black has also a real threat of taking on h3 and attacking the g2-pawn. Do we take back on d6, or continue the attack with ...gxh3? }
26... gxh3
{ Since  27.dxc7?  is not a real threat because of  27...Qg5  , White has to react on the kingside. }
27. Kh2
{ The king leaves the dangerous g-file and prepares the defense by Rg1. Black wants to open up the h- and g-files. }
27... hxg2 28. Rg1
{ Now, we may think about the queenside after this tactical skirmish. } 28...
cxd6 29. Nc6
{ The knight has to come back from the edge of the board. Giving up our light-squared bishop for the c6-knight is not advisable, so let's pin this knight! }
29... Qc7 30. Rxg2
{ It is time to activate the rooks, we need to find a suitable open file for them. }
30... Ra8 31. Rxa8 Rxa8
{ Black has an extra h5-pawn, but the pieces are not so active, so White has compensation, but not more than that. }
