[SetUp "1"]

{ White just trapped the b8-rook, it cannot run away. The knight has already penetrated to c7, which is an excellent square, sometimes Ne6 may come.  Let's turn our attention to the kingside. The g3-pawn is wonderful, there are always mating threats with ...Qh4 and ...Qxh2 mate. In this case, White's best defense is Bg1. So taking on b8 wouldn't be the best idea because White would give up the best defender.  Now Black's task is to stop the bishop's retreat to g1, how can we do that? }
20... b6
{ ∆ ...Rb7. This is one of the most spectacular sacrifices! Black forces White to take a whole rook by closing the g1-a7 diagonal. }
21. Bxb8
{ 21.h3?  loses a piece after  21...Rb7  ,  with a double attack. We sacrificed the rook, but there is no Bg1 defense anymore. How can we get close to the h2-pawn? }
21... Nxe4
{ The second sacrifice is typical, opening up the d8-h4 diagonal for the queen and threatening ...Qh4. }
22. Ne6
{ White has to neutralize the pressure on the h3-c8 diagonal.  22.h3  Qh4  23.Ne6  transposes to game continuation. }
22... Qh4 23. h3
{ If the bishop cannot sacrifice itself on h3, then comes the knight to fulfill its duty. }
23... Bxe6 { The strong intruder on e6 has to be eliminated. } 24. dxe6
{ The target is the same, the weak h3-pawn. } 24... Ng5
{ Black now has a lot of threats: ...Nxh3, ...Nxe6, ...e5-e4. } 25. Nf2
{ White wants to sacrifice a knight and a rook back... } 25... gxf2 26. Rxf2
{ White sacrifices a knight and after that a rook, but do we take it? } 26...
Rxb8
{ Black has to eliminate the active bishop instead of the passive rook.   26...Qxf2?  is not good on account of  27.Bxd6  . Black has still got a nice plan of pushing the e-pawn.   After  26...Rxb8  27.Qxd6  ,  both rooks are hanging, what to do?  27...Re8  ,  Black keeps the defensive rook, the one on f2 still looks pathetic.  28.Qxb6  e4⩱  and materially, it is not bad for White, but Black continues the strong attack. }
*

