{ Black has sacrificed a pawn on the kingside and has pressure on the semi-opened g-file and on the dark squares. On the other hand, the a8-rook and the important c8-bishop are attacked. Do we bother with the rook or simply continue our attack on the other flank? }
27... Nh5
{ Black ignores the hanging rook, brings the knight into the attack, emphasizing the pressure on the dark squares, and opens up the diagonal of the queen to g5. }
28. Nxa8
{ Black's major plan is creating a battery on the semi-opened g-file by ...Qg5, but the c8-bishop is hanging. Do we even ignore that piece as well? }
28... Qg5
{ It is unbelievable, but Black sacrifices the bishop as well, it can even be taken with check!  28...Bd7  was also possible, but we want to show the real beauty of the King's Indian! }
29. Rxc8+ Kh7 30. Rf2
{ White has an extra rook and a piece, but Black has an annoying pressure on the dark squares f4, g3, h4. }
30... Bxh2+ 31. Kxh2 Qg3+
{ Be careful! The automatic replies in chess may backfire! } 32. Kh1
{ 32.Kg1  runs into  32...h3  . } 32... Qxf2
{ The difference is that here   32...h3?  allows the successful defense with  33.Qg1!  Black's attack seems frightening, but if White plays precisely, then the position is equal.   After  32...Qxf2  33.Qg1  is the main idea of the defense.  33...Ng3+  34.Kh2  Qxe2  and White has to play carefully to avoid losing the game.  35.Rc7  , exchanging the rooks is the only chance of avoiding the mating attack.  35...Nf1+  36.Kh1  Ng3+  , when both players need to agree on the draw.  37.Kh2  , with a repetition of moves. }
*

