32. Kg1
{ Protecting the f2-rook is the move almost everyone would play in time trouble. Or even in a classical game?! Now Black's attack crashes through! }
32... h3 { ∆ ...h2 and the f2-rook falls anyway. } 33. Rc7
{ White wants to exchange the attacking g7-rook. } 33... h2+ 34. Kh1 Rxc7 35.
Nxc7
{ Now comes the big surprise. In a practical game, Black can easily go astray! }
35... Qh4
{ ∆ ...Ng3 mate. What a wonderful move! The 'natural'  35...Qxf2  throws away the win after  36.Kxh2  . }
36. g4 { Clearing the way for the white king to g2. } 36... Ng3+ 37. Kg2 h1=Q+
38. Qxh1 Nxh1
{ Black is clearly better.   After  39.Rf1  Ng3  40.Rf2  ,  the g3-knight looks trapped so it seems that it has to exchange the bad bishop.  40...Nh5  is a beautiful escape, Black exchanges the knights!   After  40...Nxe2  41.Rxe2  , White can build up a fortress. Beware of unprotected pieces!  41.gxh5  Qg5+  42.Kf1  Qc1+  43.Kg2  Qxc7∓  and Black is much better in the endgame. }
