{ Black has already sacrificed a piece and has some attack on the kingside. The a6-queen and the b5-knight are far away from the king and the f1-rook is hanging.  However, the weak spot in White's camp is the g3-pawn, Black has already a battery on the semi-opened g-file. How can we attack that weakness with more pieces? }
28... Be3 { Is it so simple? Just try to deflect the defensive bishop! } 29.
Nxd6
{ 29.Bxe3?  loses outright to  29...Qxg3  and too many white pieces are hanging. @@StartFEN@@6rk/6qp/Q2p1n2/1N1Pp3/4P2N/4bBPb/1P3B2/5RK1 w - - 1 29@@EndFEN@@  29.Bg2  Qxg3  30.Nxd6  transposes to the main line. }
29... Qxg3+ 30. Bg2 { This is the only defense. } 30... Qxh4 31. Nf7+
{ Forcing the black king to close the g-file. } 31... Kg7 32. Bxe3 Kxf7 33.
Qb7+ { With the same idea: the king has to go to the g-file. } 33... Kg6 34.
Rf2
{ White finally overprotects the weak g2-bishop. Now comes again an extraordinary move, with the idea of opening the g-file! }
34... Kh5
{ As Steinitz declared: "I am bravely fighting with my king!" Black has got a nice attack, but if White plays well it is only equal.   After  35.Qf7+  Rg6  36.Rxf6  ,  White has to take the knight, the g6-rook is pinned.  36...Qe1+  ,  Black is winning the piece back.  37.Rf1  Qxe3+  38.Rf2  Bxg2  39.Qxh7+  ,  White again forces the black king to the g-file.  39...Kg5  40.Kxg2  and finally, an equal endgame arises, where both kings are vulnerable.  40...Qxe4+  41.Kg1  Qe1+  42.Kg2  Qe4+=  ,  with a repetition of moves. }
