29. Qxd6 { White loses in a nice way. How? } 29... Qxg3+ 30. Kh1
{ Orlov-Joos, Vancouver 1997. It seems that White was right, the queen and the knight are hanging. How can Black solve this problem? }
30... Qf4
{ We usually seek forceful attacking moves, checks, and captures, and not a quiet retreat. Now the f1-rook and the f2-bishop are hanging. }
31. Ng6+
{ 31.Bxe3  leaves  the h4-knight unattended, and after  31...Qxh4  , Black wins outright. On @@StartFEN@@6rk/7p/3Q1n2/1N1Pp3/4Pq1N/4bB1b/1P3B2/5R1K w - - 2 31@@EndFEN@@  31.Rg1  , the simple answer is  31...Bxf2  32.Rxg8  Nxg8  , with an easy win. }
31... Rxg6 32. Qf8+ Rg8 33. Bxe3
{ That was the plan, both queens are hanging, but Black certainly avoids the exchange of the most valuable piece. }
33... Qh4
{ The queen and the rook are hanging, and there are mating threats; the game is over. }
