{ White hasn't done much so far on the queenside, the only achievement is a beautiful knight on c7. Black has already opened the h-file and attacks the weak g2-pawn on the semi-opened g-file. The big question is how to bring the queen into the attack in a forced way. }
29... Ne8
{ This is the rare occasion when the f6-knight instead of sacrificing itself goes backwards. However, this also opens up the h4-d8 diagonal for the queen and challenges the strong knight on c7. }
30. Bxa5 { Deflecting the a7-rook from the 7th rank. } 30... Rxa5 31. Nxe8
{ The c8-bishop is hanging, as well as the e8-knight. A difficult move is coming because Black usually doesn't even look at the queenside, but now we have to deal with our hanging bishop. }
31... Ba6
{ The bishop creates nasty threats on the f1-a6 diagonal, and the e8-knight is still hanging. }
32. Nc7
{ White is happy to sacrifice an exchange, when the king is relatively safe. Although many pieces are hanging, Black has to return to the original plan, attacking on the kingside. }
32... Rxg2+
{ This is again a beautiful rook sacrifice, when the motif is different to the other lines where the rook is on a7; the a5-rook cannot join the attack. }
33. Kxg2 Qg5+ 34. Kh1 { Let's come with our queen closer to the king. } 34...
Qh4+ 35. Kg2 Qg3+
{ Now we have improved the position of the queen, so we are ready to continue the attack against the white king. }
